# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: land-ethic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has had over two million copies printed and has been translated into at least fourteen languages.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] It has informed and changed the environmental movement and stimulated a widespread interest in ecology as a science.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] In the original publishing, the book begins with a set of essays under the heading "Sand County Almanac," which is divided into twelve segments, one for each month.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] These essays mostly follow the changes in the ecology on Leopold's farm near Baraboo, Wisconsin.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] (There is, in fact, no "Sand County" in Wisconsin.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] The term "sand counties" refers to a section of the state marked by sandy soils).
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] There are anecdotes and observations about flora and fauna reactions to the seasons as well as mentions of conservation topics.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] The second section of the book, "Sketches Here and There," shifts the rhetorical focus from time to place.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] The essays are thematically organized around farms and wildernesses in Canada, Mexico and the United States.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] Some of these essays are autobiographical.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] "Red Legs Kicking," for example, recounts Leopold's boyhood experience of hunting in Iowa.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] The seminal essay "Thinking Like a Mountain" recalls another hunting experience later in life that was formative for Leopold's later views.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] Here Leopold describes the death of a she-wolf killed by his party during a time when conservationists were operating under the assumption that elimination of top predators would make game plentiful.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] The essay provides a non-technical characterization of the trophic cascade where the removal of single species carries serious implications for the rest of the ecosystem.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] The book ends with a section of philosophical essays grouped together under the heading "The Upshot".
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] Here Leopold explores ironies of conservation: in order to promote wider appreciation of wild nature and engender necessary political support, one encourages recreational usage of wilderness that ultimately destroys it.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] Musings on "trophies" contrasts the way that some need a physical specimen to prove their conquest into the wilderness, though photographs may be less damaging than a trophy head to be mounted on the wall.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] He suggests that the best trophy is the experience of wilderness itself, along with its character-building aspects.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] Leopold also rails against the way that policy makers need to find an economic motive for conservation.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] In the concluding essay, "The Land Ethic", Leopold delves into a more appropriate rationale for conservation.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] In "The Ecological Conscience" section, he wrote: "Conservation is a state of harmony between men and land." Leopold felt it was generally agreed that more conservation education was needed; however quantity and content were up for debate.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] He believed that land is not a commodity to be possessed; rather, humans must have mutual respect for Earth in order not to destroy it.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] He philosophizes that humans will cease to be free if they have no wild spaces in which to roam.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] In a 1990 poll of the membership by the American Nature Study Society, *A Sand County Almanac* and Rachel Carson's *Silent Spring* stand alone as the two most venerated and significant environmental books of the 20th century.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] The book was little noticed when published but, during the environmental awakening of the 1970s, a paperback edition turned into a surprise bestseller.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has had immense popular influence and has been described as: "one of the benchmark titles of the ecological movement", "a major influence on American attitudes toward our natural environment", "recognized as a classic piece of outdoor literature, rivaling Thoreau's *Walden*".
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has also had great influence on environmental thinkers: "along with *Walden* and Rachel Carson’s *Silent Spring*, one of the main intellectual underpinnings of environmentalism in America".
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] The book has "attracted such overwhelming attention from environmental philosophers as a source of inspiration and ideas".
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] Leopold's home, Aldo Leopold Shack and Farm, was listed on the U.S.
[src:land-ethic/a-sand-county-almanac] National Register of Historic Places in 1978, and was uplisted to National Historic Landmark status in 2009.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Some scholars suggest that agrarianism espouses the superiority of rural society to urban society and the independent farmer as superior to the paid worker, and sees farming as a way of life that can shape the ideal social values.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] It stresses the superiority of a simpler rural life in comparison to the complexity of urban life.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The philosophical roots of agrarianism include European and Chinese philosophers.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The Chinese school of Agriculturalism (农家/農家) was a philosophy that advocated peasant utopian communalism and egalitarianism.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In societies influenced by Confucianism that had as its foundation that humans are innately good, the farmer was considered an esteemed productive member of society, but merchants who made money were looked down upon.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] That influenced European intellectuals like François Quesnay, an avid Confucianist and advocate of China's agrarian policies, in forming the French agrarian philosophy of physiocracy.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The physiocrats, along with the ideas of John Locke and the Romantic Era, formed the basis of modern European and American agrarianism.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] , du Pont advocated low tariffs and free trade.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Physiocracy (French: *physiocratie*; from the Greek for "government of nature") is an economic theory developed by a group of 18th-century Age of Enlightenment French economists.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] They believed that the wealth of nations derived solely from the value of "land agriculture" or "land development" and that agricultural products should be highly priced.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Their theories originated in France and were most popular during the second half of the 18th century.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Physiocracy became one of the first well-developed theories of economics.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] François Quesnay (1694–1774), the Marquis de Mirabeau (1715–1789) and Anne-Robert-Jacques Turgot (1727–1781) dominated the movement, which immediately preceded the first modern school, classical economics, which began with the publication of Adam Smith's *The Wealth of Nations* in 1776.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The physiocrats made a significant contribution in their emphasis on productive work as the source of national wealth.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] This contrasted with earlier schools, in particular mercantilism, which often focused on the ruler's wealth, accumulation of gold, or the balance of trade.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] For the physiocrats, however, only agricultural labor created this value in the products of society.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] All "industrial" and non-agricultural labors were "unproductive appendages" to agricultural labor.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Quesnay was likely influenced by his medical training, particularly by the work of William Harvey who explained how blood flow and the circulatory system is vital to the human body; Quesnay held that the circulation of wealth was vital to the economy.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Societies at the time were also overwhelmingly agrarian.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] This may be why they viewed agriculture as the primary source of a nation's wealth.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] This is an idea that Quesnay purported to demonstrate with data, comparing a workshop to a farm.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] He analyzed "how money flowed between the three classes of farmers, proprietors, and artisans, in the same mechanical way that blood flows between different organs" and claimed only the farm produced a surplus that added to the nation's wealth.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Physiocrats viewed the production of goods and services as equivalent to the consumption of the agricultural surplus, since human or animal muscle provided the main source of power and all energy derived from the surplus from agricultural production.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Profit in capitalist production was really only the "rent" obtained by the owner of the land on which the agricultural production took place.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] "The physiocrats damned cities for their artificiality and praised what they considered to be more natural styles of living.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] They celebrated farmers." They called themselves *les Économistes*, but are generally referred to as "physiocrats" to distinguish their beliefs from the many schools of economic thought that followed.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The United States president Thomas Jefferson was an agrarian who based his ideas about the budding American democracy around the notion that farmers are "the most valuable citizens" and the truest republicans.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Jefferson and his support base were committed to American republicanism, which they saw as being in opposition to monarchy, aristocracy, clericalism and corruption, and which prioritized morality and virtue, exemplified by the "yeoman farmer", "planters", and the "plain folk".
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In praising the rural farmfolk, the Jeffersonians felt that financiers, bankers and industrialists created "cesspools of corruption" in the cities and should thus be avoided.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The Jeffersonians sought to align the American economy more with agriculture than industry.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Part of their motive to do so was Jefferson's fear that the over-industrialization of America would create a class of wage slaves who relied on their employers for income and sustenance.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In turn, these workers would cease to be independent voters as their vote could be manipulated by said employers.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] There is general agreement that the substantial United States' federal policy of offering land grants (such as thousands of gifts of land to veterans) had a positive impact on economic development in the 19th century.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Agrarian socialism is a form of agrarianism that is anti-capitalist in nature and seeks to introduce socialist economic systems in their stead.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] One notable agrarian socialists was Emiliano Zapata, a leading figure in the Mexican Revolution.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] As the leader of the Liberation Army of the South, his group of revolutionaries fought on behalf of the Mexican peasants, whom they saw as exploited by the landowning classes.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Zapata published the Plan of Ayala, which called for significant land reforms and land redistribution in Mexico as part of the revolution.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Zapata was killed and his forces crushed over the course of the Revolution, but his political ideas lived on in the form of Zapatismo.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Zapatismo would form the basis for neozapatismo, the ideology of the modern Zapatista Army of National Liberation.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Known as *Ejército Zapatista de Liberación Nacional* or EZLN in Spanish, EZLN is a far-left, libertarian socialist political and militant group that emerged in the state of Chiapas in southmost Mexico in 1994.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] EZLN and Neozapatismo, as explicit in their name, seek to revive the agrarian socialist movement of Zapata, but fuse it with new elements such as a commitment to indigenous rights and community-level decision making.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Maoism, the far-left ideology of Mao Zedong and his followers, places a heavy emphasis on the role of peasants in its goals.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In contrast to other Marxist schools of thought which normally seek to acquire the support of urban workers, Maoism sees the peasantry as key.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] During the Chinese Civil War and the Second Sino-Japanese War, Mao and the Chinese Communist Party made extensive use of peasants and rural bases in their military tactics, often eschewing the cities.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Following the eventual victory of the Communist Party in both wars, the countryside and how it should be run remained a focus for Mao.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In 1958, Mao launched the Great Leap Forward, a social and economic campaign which, amongst other things, altered many aspects of rural Chinese life.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] It introduced mandatory collective farming and forced the peasantry to organize itself into communal living units which were known as people's communes.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] These communes, which consisted of 5,000 people on average, were expected to meet high production quotas while the peasants who lived on them adapted to this radically new way of life.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The communes were run as co-operatives where wages and money were replaced by work points.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Peasants who criticised this new system were persecuted as "rightists" and "counter-revolutionaries".
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Leaving the communes was forbidden and escaping from them was difficult or impossible, and those who attempted it were subjected to party-orchestrated "public struggle sessions," which further jeopardized their survival.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] These public criticism sessions were often used to intimidate the peasants into obeying local officials and they often devolved into little more than public beatings.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] On the communes, experiments were conducted in order to find new methods of planting crops, efforts were made to construct new irrigation systems on a massive scale, and the communes were all encouraged to produce steel backyard furnaces as part of an effort to increase steel production.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Similarly, the experimentation with the crops did not produce results.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In addition to this the Four Pests Campaign was launched, in which the peasants were called upon to destroy sparrows and other wild birds that ate crop seeds, in order to protect fields.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Pest birds were shot down or scared away from landing until they dropped from exhaustion.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] This campaign resulted in an ecological disaster that saw an explosion of the vermin population, especially crop-eating insects, which was consequently not in danger of being killed by predators.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] None of these new systems were working, but local leaders did not dare to state this, instead, they falsified reports so as not to be punished for failing to meet the quotas.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In many cases they stated that they were greatly exceeding their quotas, and in turn, the Chinese state developed a completely false sense of success with regard to the commune system.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] All of this culminated in the Great Chinese Famine, which began in 1959, lasted 3 years, and saw an estimated 15 to 30 million Chinese people die.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] A combination of bad weather and the new, failed farming techniques that were introduced by the state led to massive shortages of food.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] By 1962, the Great Leap Forward was declared to be at an end.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In the late 1960s and early 1970s, Mao once again radically altered life in rural China with the launching of the Down to the Countryside Movement.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] As a response to the Great Chinese Famine, the Chinese President Liu Shaoqi began "sending down" urban youths to rural China in order to recover its population losses and alleviate overcrowding in the cities.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] However, Mao turned the practice into a political crusade, declaring that the sending down would strip the youth of any bourgeois tendencies by forcing them to learn from the unprivileged rural peasants.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In reality, it was the Communist Party's attempt to reign in the Red Guards, who had become uncontrollable during the course of the Cultural Revolution.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] 10% of the 1970 urban population of China was sent out to remote rural villages, often in Inner Mongolia.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The villages, which were still poorly recovering from the effects of the Great Chinese Famine, did not have the excess resources that were needed to support the newcomers.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Furthermore, the so-called "sent-down youth" had no agricultural experience and as a result, they were unaccustomed to the harsh lifestyle that existed in the countryside, and their unskilled labor in the villages provided little benefit to the agricultural sector.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] As a result, many of the sent-down youth died in the countryside.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The relocation of the youths was originally intended to be permanent, but by the end of the Cultural Revolution, the Communist Party relented and some of those who had the capacity to return to the cities were allowed to do so.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In imitation of Mao's policies, the Khmer Rouge of Cambodia (who were heavily funded and supported by the People's Republic of China) created their own version of the Great Leap Forward which was known as "Maha Lout Ploh".
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] With the Great Leap Forward as its model, it had similarly disastrous effects, contributing to what is now known as the Cambodian genocide.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] As a part of the Maha Lout Ploh, the Khmer Rouge sought to create an entirely agrarian socialist society by forcibly relocating 100,000 people to move from Cambodia's cities into newly created communes.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The Khmer Rouge leader, Pol Pot sought to "purify" the country by setting it back to "Year Zero", freeing it from "corrupting influences".
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Besides trying to completely de-urbanize Cambodia, ethnic minorities were slaughtered along with anyone else who was suspected of being a "reactionary" or a member of the "bourgeoisie", to the point that wearing glasses was seen as grounds for execution.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The killings were only brought to an end when Cambodia was invaded by the neighboring socialist nation of Vietnam, whose army toppled the Khmer Rouge.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] However, with Cambodia's entire society and economy in disarray, including its agricultural sector, the country still plunged into renewed famine due to vast food shortages.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] However, as international journalists began to report on the situation and send images of it out to the world, a massive international response was provoked, leading to one of the most concentrated relief efforts of its time.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Peasant parties first appeared across Eastern Europe between 1860 and 1910, when commercialized agriculture and world market forces disrupted traditional rural society, and the railway and growing literacy facilitated the work of roving organizers.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Agrarian parties advocated land reforms to redistribute land on large estates among those who work it.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] They also wanted village cooperatives to keep the profit from crop sales in local hands and credit institutions to underwrite needed improvements.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Many peasant parties were also nationalist parties because peasants often worked their land for the benefit of landlords of different ethnicity.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Peasant parties rarely had any power before World War I but some became influential in the interwar era, especially in Bulgaria and Czechoslovakia.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] For a while, in the 1920s and the 1930s, there was a Green International (International Agrarian Bureau) based on the peasant parties in Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, Poland, and Serbia.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] It functioned primarily as an information center that spread the ideas of agrarianism and combating socialism on the left and landlords on the right and never launched any significant activities.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In Bulgaria, the Bulgarian Agrarian National Union (BZNS) was organized in 1899 to resist taxes and build cooperatives.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] BZNS came to power in 1919 and introduced many economic, social, and legal reforms.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] However, conservative forces crushed BZNS in a 1923 coup and assassinated its leader, Aleksandar Stamboliyski (1879–1923).
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] BZNS was made into a communist puppet group until 1989, when it reorganized as a genuine party.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In Czechoslovakia, the Republican Party of Agricultural and Smallholder People often shared power in parliament as a partner in the five-party pětka coalition.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The party's leader, Antonín Švehla (1873–1933), was prime minister several times.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] It was consistently the strongest party, forming and dominating coalitions.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] It moved beyond its original agrarian base to reach middle-class voters.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The party was banned by the National Front after the Second World War.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In France, the Hunting, Fishing, Nature, Tradition party is a moderate conservative, agrarian party, reaching a peak of 4.23% in the 2002 French presidential election.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] It would later on become affiliated to France's main conservative party, Union for a Popular Movement.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] More recently, the Resistons! movement of Jean Lassalle espoused agrarianism.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In Hungary, the first major agrarian party, the small-holders party was founded in 1908.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The party became part of the government in the 1920s but lost influence in the government.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] A new party, the Independent Smallholders, Agrarian Workers and Civic Party was established in 1930 with a more radical program representing larger scale land redistribution initiatives.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] They implemented this program together with the other coalition parties after WWII.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] However, after 1949 the party was outlawed when a one-party system was introduced.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] They became part of the government again 1990–1994, and 1998–2002 after which they lost political support.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The ruling Fidesz party has an agrarian faction, and promotes agrarian interest since 2010 with the emphasis now placed on supporting larger family farms versus small-holders.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In the late 19th century, the Irish National Land League aimed to abolish landlordism in Ireland and enable tenant farmers to own the land they worked on.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The "Land War" of 1878–1909 led to the Irish Land Acts, ending absentee landlords and ground rent and redistributing land among peasant farmers.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Post-independence, the Farmers' Party operated in the Irish Free State from 1922, folding into the National Centre Party in 1932.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] It was mostly supported by wealthy farmers in the east of Ireland.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Clann na Talmhan (Family of the Land; also called the *National Agricultural Party*) was founded in 1938.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] They focused more on the poor smallholders of the west, supporting land reclamation, afforestation, social democracy and rates reform.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] They formed part of the governing coalition of the Government of the 13th Dáil and Government of the 15th Dáil.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Economic improvement in the 1960s saw farmers vote for other parties and Clann na Talmhan disbanded in 1965.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In Kazakhstan, the Peasants' Union, originally a communist organization, was formed as one of first agrarian parties in independent Kazakhstan and would win four seats in the 1994 legislative election.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The Agrarian Party of Kazakhstan, led by Romin Madinov, was founded in 1999, which favored the privatization of agricultural land, developments towards rural infrastructure, as well as changes in the tax system in agrarian economy.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] From there, the bloc remained short-lived as it would merge with the ruling Nur Otan party in 2006.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Several other parties in Kazakhstan over the years have embraced agrarian policies in their programs in an effort to appeal towards a large rural Kazakh demographic base, which included Amanat, ADAL, and Respublica.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Since late 2000s, the Auyl party remains the largest and most influential agrarian-oriented party in Kazakhstan, as its presidential candidate Jiguli Dairabaev had become the second-place frontrunner in the 2022 presidential election after sweeping 3.4% of the vote.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In the 2023 legislative election, the Auyl party for the first time was represented the parliament after winning nine seats in the lower chamber Mäjilis.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The party raises rural issues in regard to decaying villages, rural development and the agro-industrial complex, the issues of social security of the rural population, and has consistently opposed the ongoing rural flight in Kazakhstan.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In Latvia, the Union of Greens and Farmers is supportive of traditional small farms and perceives them as more environmentally friendly than large-scale farming: Nature is threatened by development, while small farms are threatened by large industrial-scale farms.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In Lithuania, the government led by the Lithuanian Farmers and Greens Union was in power between 2016 and 2020.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The Nordic agrarian parties, also referred to as Scandinavian agrarian parties or agrarian liberal parties, are agrarian political parties that belong to a political tradition particular to the Nordic countries.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Positioning themselves in the centre of the political spectrum, but fulfilling roles distinctive to Nordic countries, they remain hard to classify by conventional political ideology.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] These parties are non-Socialist and typically combine a commitment to small businesses, rural issues and political decentralisation, and, at times, scepticism towards the European Union.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The parties have divergent views on the free market and environmentalism.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Internationally, they are most commonly aligned to the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe (ALDE) and the Liberal International.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Historically farmers' parties, a declining farmer population after the Second World War made them broaden their scope to other issues and sections of society.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] At this time three of them renamed themselves to Centre Party, with the Finnish Centre Party being the last to do so, in 1965.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In the modern period, the main agrarian parties are the Centre Party in Sweden, *Venstre* in Denmark, Centre Party in Finland, Centre Party in Norway and Progressive Party in Iceland.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In Poland, the Polish People's Party (*Polskie Stronnictwo Ludowe*, PSL) traces its tradition to an agrarian party in Austro-Hungarian-controlled Galician Poland.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] After the fall of the communist regime, PSL's biggest success came in 1993 elections, where it won 132 out of 460 parliamentary seats.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Since then, PSL's support has steadily declined, until 2019, when they formed Polish Coalition with an anti-establishment, direct democracy Kukiz'15 party, and managed to get 8.5% of popular vote.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Moreover, PSL tends to get much better results in local elections.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In 2014 elections they have managed to get 23.88% of votes.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The right-wing Law and Justice party has also become supportive of agrarian policies in recent years and polls show that most of their support comes from rural areas.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] AGROunia resembles the features of agrarianism.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In Romania, older party parties from Transylvania, Moldavia, and Wallachia merged to become the National Peasants' Party (PNȚ) in 1926.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Iuliu Maniu (1873–1953) was a prime minister with an agrarian cabinet from 1928 to 1930 and briefly in 1932–1933, but the Great Depression made proposed reforms impossible.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The communist administration dissolved the party in 1947 (along with other historical parties such as the National Liberal Party), but it reformed in 1989 after they fell from power.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The reformed party, which also incorporated elements of Christian democracy in its ideology, governed Romania as part of the Romanian Democratic Convention (CDR) between 1996 and 2000.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In Serbia, Nikola Pašić (1845–1926) and his People's Radical Party dominated Serbian politics after 1903.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The party also monopolized power in Yugoslavia from 1918 to 1929.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] During the dictatorship of the 1930s, the prime minister was from that party.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In Ukraine, the Radical Party of Oleh Lyashko has promised to purify the country of oligarchs "with a pitchfork".
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In land law the heyday of English, Irish (and thus Welsh) agrarianism was c.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The heyday was eroded by hundreds of Acts of Parliament to expressly permit enclosure, chiefly from 1650 to the 1810s.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Politicians standing strongly as reactionaries to this included the Levellers, those anti-industrialists (Luddites) going beyond opposing new weaving technology and, later, radicals such as William Cobbett.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] A high level of net national or local self-sufficiency has a strong base in campaigns and movements.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In the 19th century such empowered advocates included Peelites and most Conservatives.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The 21st century has seen decarbonisation already in electricity markets.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Following protests and charitable lobbying local food has seen growing market share, sometimes backed by wording in public policy papers and manifestos.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The UK has many sustainability-prioritising businesses, green charity campaigns, events and lobby groups ranging from espousing allotment gardens (hobby community farming) through to a clear policy of local food and/or self-sustainability models.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The National Party of Australia (formerly called the Country Party), from the 1920s to the 1970s, promulgated its version of agrarianism, which it called "countrymindedness".
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The goal was to enhance the status of the graziers (operators of big sheep stations) and small farmers and justified subsidies for them.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The New Zealand Liberal Party aggressively promoted agrarianism in its heyday (1891–1912).
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The landed gentry and aristocracy ruled Britain at this time.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] New Zealand never had an aristocracy but its wealthy landowners largely controlled politics before 1891.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The Liberal Party set out to change that by a policy it called "populism." Richard Seddon had proclaimed the goal as early as 1884: "It is the rich and the poor; it is the wealthy and the landowners against the middle and labouring classes.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] That, Sir, shows the real political position of New Zealand." The Liberal strategy was to create a large class of small landowning farmers who supported Liberal ideals.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The Liberal government also established the basis of the later welfare state such as old age pensions and developed a system for settling industrial disputes, which was accepted by both employers and trade unions.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] In 1893, it extended voting rights to women, making New Zealand the first country in the world to do so.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] To obtain land for farmers, the Liberal government from 1891 to 1911 purchased 3,100,000 acres (1,300,000 ha) of Maori land.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The government also purchased 1,300,000 acres (530,000 ha) from large estate holders for subdivision and closer settlement by small farmers.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The Advances to Settlers Act (1894) provided low-interest mortgages, and the agriculture department disseminated information on the best farming methods.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The Liberals proclaimed success in forging an egalitarian, anti-monopoly land policy.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The policy built up support for the Liberal Party in rural North Island electorates.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] By 1903, the Liberals were so dominant that there was no longer an organized opposition in Parliament.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The United States and Canada both saw a rise of Agrarian-oriented parties in the early twentieth century as economic troubles motivated farming communities to become politically active.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] It has been proposed that different responses to agrarian protest largely determined the course of power generated by these newly energized rural factions.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] These reactions may have helped determine the outcome of agrarian power and political associations in the US and Canada.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Economic desperation experienced by farmers across the state of Kansas in the nineteenth century spurred the creation of The People's Party in 1890, and soon-after would gain control of the governor's office in 1892.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] This party, consisting of a mix of Democrats, Socialists, Populists, and Fusionists, would find itself buckling from internal conflict regarding the unlimited coinage of silver.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] The Populists permanently lost power in 1898.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Oklahoma farmers considered their political activity during the early twentieth century due to the outbreak of war, depressed crop prices, and an inhibited sense of progression towards owning their own farms.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Tenancy had been reportedly as high as 55% in Oklahoma by 1910.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] This agrarian-backed Socialist party would win numerous offices, causing a panic within the local Democratic party.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] This agrarian-Socialist movement would be inhibited by voter suppression laws aimed at reducing the participation of voters of color, as well as national wartime policies intended to disrupt political elements considered subversive.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] During the 1930s and 1940s many farmers supported the Wisconsin Progressive Party - National Progressives.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Agrarianism during this time was often linked with progressive politics.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Agrarianism is similar to but not identical with the back-to-the-land movement.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Agrarianism concentrates on the fundamental goods of the earth, on communities of more limited economic and political scale than in modern society, and on simple living, even when the shift involves questioning the "progressive" character of some recent social and economic developments.
[src:land-ethic/agrarianism] Thus, agrarianism is not industrial farming, with its specialization on products and industrial scale.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold was influential in the development of modern environmental ethics and in the movement for wilderness conservation.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] His ethics of nature and wildlife preservation had a profound impact on the environmental movement, with his ecocentric or holistic ethics regarding land.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He emphasized biodiversity and ecology and was a founder of the science of wildlife management.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Rand Aldo Leopold was born in Burlington, Iowa, on January 11, 1887.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] His father, Carl Leopold, was a businessman who made walnut desks and was first cousin to his wife, Clara Starker.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Charles Starker, who was Carl's father and Clara's uncle, came to the United States from Germany and studied engineering and architecture.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Rand Aldo was named after two of his father's business partners—C.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Rand and Aldo Sommers—although he eventually dropped the use of "Rand".
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The Leopold family included younger siblings Mary Luize, Carl Starker, and Frederic.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold's first language was German, although he mastered English at an early age.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold's early life was highlighted by the outdoors.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Carl would take his children on excursions into the woods and taught his oldest son woodcraft and hunting.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Aldo showed an aptitude for observation, spending hours counting and cataloging birds near his home.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] His sister Mary later said that even as a young child, "He was very much an outdoorsman, even in his extreme youth.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He was always out climbing around the bluffs, or going down to the river, or going across the river into the woods." He attended Prospect Hill Elementary, where he ranked at the top of his class, and then, the overcrowded Burlington High School.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Every August, the family vacationed in Michigan on the forested Marquette Island in Lake Huron, which the children took to exploring.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In 1900, Gifford Pinchot, head of the new Division of Forestry in the Department of Agriculture, donated money to Yale University to begin one of the nation's first forestry schools.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Hearing of this development, teenage Leopold decided he wanted to become a forester.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] His parents agreed to let him attend The Lawrenceville School, a preparatory college in New Jersey, to improve his chances of admission to Yale.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The Burlington High School principal wrote in a reference letter to the headmaster at Lawrenceville saying that Leopold was "as earnest a boy as we have in school... painstaking in his work....
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Moral character above reproach." He arrived at his new school in January 1904, shortly before he turned 17.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He was considered an attentive student, although he was again drawn to the outdoors.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Lawrenceville was suitably rural, and Leopold spent much time mapping the area and studying its wildlife.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold studied at the Lawrenceville School for a year, during which time he was accepted to Yale.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Since the Yale School of Forestry granted only graduate degrees, Leopold first enrolled in Sheffield Scientific School's preparatory forestry courses for his undergraduate studies, in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] While Leopold was able to explore the woods and fields of Lawrenceville daily, sometimes to the detriment of his studying, at Yale he had little opportunity to do so; his studies and social life made his outdoor trips few and far between.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold graduated from the Yale Forestry School in 1909.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In 1909, Leopold was assigned to the Forest Service's District 3 in the Arizona and New Mexico territories.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] At first, he was a forest assistant at the Apache National Forest in the Arizona Territory.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In 1911, he was transferred to the Carson National Forest in northern New Mexico.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold was stationed in New Mexico until 1924 because he was developing the first comprehensive management plan for the Grand Canyon, writing the Forest Service's first game and fish handbook, and proposing Gila Wilderness Area, the first wilderness area in the Forest Service system.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Furthermore, Leopold encouraged many changes within New Mexico and Arizona through his time spent in the region developing these plans.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In 1916, Leopold conducted a speaking tour across New Mexico to encourage the formation of wildlife protection associations among local sportsmen.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The tour began in Silver City, where Leopold met Miles W.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Buford, who went on to establish the Sportsmen's Association of Southwestern New Mexico.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold proposed the creation of a statewide organization, the New Mexico Game Protection Association (NMGPA), which gained support in several cities including Rincon, El Paso, Alamogordo, Cloudcroft, Carlsbad, Roswell, and Albuquerque.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In March 1916, the NMGPA held its first convention, attracting over 1,000 members.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The association adopted three goals: removing game warden appointments from political influence, establishing game refuges within national forests, and implementing a balance of predators.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Following the formation of the NMGPA, Leopold returned to his duties with the U.S.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] After the passage of the Term Permit Act, he began siting and surveying locations in Arizona for private recreational development.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] During this time, he also promoted and helped establish Game Protection Associations in Arizona towns such as Flagstaff, Springerville, Tucson, and Payson.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In January 1918, Leopold became Secretary of the Albuquerque Chamber of Commerce.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In this role, he supported various initiatives, including the inclusion of labor organizations in the chamber, the promotion of Hispanic and Pueblo architectural styles, and the drainage of parts of the Rio Grande Valley to expand agricultural land.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold rejoined the Forest Service on August 1, 1919, as Assistant District Forester in Charge of Operations, overseeing Region 3, which included 11 national forests.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] During this period, he became concerned with soil erosion in areas such as the Prescott and Carson National Forests.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In December 1923, he authored *The Watershed Handbook*, a guide for field staff addressing watershed management and recommending the regulation of livestock based on watershed conditions.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Just a few months into his new role, Leopold's superior, District Forester Paul Redington, left Region 3 and was succeeded by Frank C.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Pooler—who openly expressed doubts about Leopold's suitability for the position.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Pooler even arranged a new post for Leopold in a different region.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] However, Leopold stood his ground and declined the offer, choosing to stay in Albuquerque and New Mexico, where his family and numerous ongoing projects were deeply rooted.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold's management plan was visionary for its time, emphasizing sustainable use and ecological preservation.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He planned to make regulations with tourism, resource protection, recreational planning, and the long-term vision of the park.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He felt that there needed to be a control of commercial enterprises, such as shops and concessions because he described them as "repugnant" to the canyon's natural character.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He suggested there should be designated areas for visitor facilities to minimize environmental disruption.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Additionally, He advocated for the cleanup of garbage and sewage to restore the Colorado River's water quality.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Previously, there was history of people dumping garbage in the river.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He emphasized preserving the canyon's geological and ecological features, including its stratified rock formations and native flora and fauna.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold's plan for recreational planning was to outline strategies for “primitive recreation,” such as hiking, hunting, and fishing, to allow visitors to experience the canyon's wilderness without degrading it.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He recommended trail development to improve access while protecting sensitive areas.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Finally, his long-term vision was to prioritized the “greatest good for the greatest number in the long run,” aligning with U.S.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He laid the groundwork for future park management by advocating for a balance between human enjoyment and ecological health.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Wildlife management was largely unregulated, with game and fish populations often depleted due to overhunting, habitat destruction, and lack of coordinated oversight.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold recognized the need for a systematic approach to manage wildlife resources.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In the handbook, Leopold detailed a section on wildlife population management where he provided a guideline for monitoring and regulating game species, such as deer, elk, and fish, to prevent overharvesting.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He emphasized sustainable hunting and fishing practices to maintain population health.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Additionally, he wrote a section on habitat conservation which he stressed the importance of preserving habitats, including forests, rivers, and wetlands, to support wildlife.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He included recommendations for mitigating the impacts of grazing and logging on game and fish habitats.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In a section about ecological balance, he introduced early concepts of predator-prey dynamics reflecting on his observations of ecological consequences when predators like wolves were eradicated.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He advocated for a holistic approach to land management considering wildlife as part of the broader ecosystem.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Forest Service rangers to collect data on wildlife populations and enforce regulations.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He proposed coordination with local communities and hunters to promote conservation awareness.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In 1921, Leopold published an article in the *Journal of Forestry* titled “The Wilderness and Its Place in Forest Recreational Policy,” arguing for the preservation of roadless areas within national forests.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He proposed the Gila as a prime candidate, envisioning it as a space free from roads, motorized vehicles, and industrial development.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He recommended setting aside 750,000 acres of the Gila National Forest headwaters, an area characterized by canyons, mesas, and diverse wildlife, including elk, deer, and trout.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold's proposal gained traction, and in 1924, the Forest Service approved the designation of 755,000 acres as the Gila Wilderness Area, the first such area in the world.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold saw the Gila as a living laboratory for ecological health, where natural processes like predator-prey dynamics could unfold without human interference.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] This reflected his early understanding of trophic cascades, later detailed in his essay “Thinking Like a Mountain.” He also valued the Gila for its cultural significance, offering a space for Americans to reconnect with the frontier experience through self-reliant recreation.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] On April 5, 1923, he was elected an associate member (now called "professional member") of the Boone and Crockett Club, a wildlife conservation organization founded by Theodore Roosevelt and George Bird Grinnell.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In 1924, he accepted transfer to the U.S.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Forest Products Laboratory in Madison, Wisconsin, and became an associate director.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In 1933, he was appointed Professor of Game Management in the Agricultural Economics Department at the University of Wisconsin, the first such professorship of wildlife management.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] At the same time he was named Research Director of the University of Wisconsin–Madison Arboretum.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold and other members of the first Arboretum Committee initiated a research agenda around re-establishing "original Wisconsin" landscape and plant communities, particularly those that predated European settlement, such as tallgrass prairie and oak savanna.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Under the Oberlaender Trust of the Carl Schurz Memorial Foundation, Leopold was part of the 1935 group of six U.S.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Forest Service associates who toured the forests of Germany and Austria.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold was invited specifically to study game management, and this was his first and only time abroad.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] His European observations would have a significant impact on his ecological thinking, leading him to view the German policies in favor of blocks of monoculture trees in straight lines as a cautionary tale leading to soil degradation and an overall loss of biodiversity.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] After 1935, Leopold was no longer working for the U.S.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Forest Service; he had left the agency in 1928 to work independently and later became a professor at the University of Wisconsin.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold married Estella Bergere, the daughter of a well known ranching family in New Mexico, in northern New Mexico in 1912 and they had five children together.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] They lived in a modest two-story home close to the UW–Madison campus.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] His children followed in his footsteps as teachers and naturalists: Aldo Starker Leopold (1913–1983) was a wildlife biologist and professor at UC Berkeley; Luna B.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold purchased 80 acres in the sand country of central Wisconsin.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The once-forested region had been logged, swept by repeated fires, overgrazed by dairy cows, and left barren.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He put his theories to work in the field and eventually set to work writing his best-selling *A Sand County Almanac* (1949) which was finished just prior to his death.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold died from a heart attack on April 21, 1948, while helping his neighbors control a grass fire by his farm in Baraboo, Wisconsin.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold's home is an official landmark of the city of Madison.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Early on, Leopold was assigned to hunt and kill bears, wolves, and mountain lions in New Mexico.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Local ranchers hated these predators because of livestock losses, but Leopold came to respect the animals.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] One day after fatally shooting a wolf, Leopold reached the animal and was transfixed by a "fierce green fire dying in her eyes." That experience changed him and put him on the path toward an ecocentric outlook.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He developed an ecological ethic that replaced the earlier wilderness ethic that stressed the need for human dominance.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] His rethinking the importance of predators in the balance of nature has resulted in the return of bears and mountain lions to New Mexico wilderness areas.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] By the early 1920s, Leopold had concluded that a particular kind of preservation should be embraced in the national forests of the American West.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He was prompted to this by the rampant building of roads to accommodate the "proliferation of the automobile" and the related increasingly heavy recreational demands placed on public lands.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He was the first to employ the term "wilderness" to describe such preservation.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Over the next two decades, he added ethical and scientific rationales to his defense of the wilderness concept.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold believed that it is easier to maintain wilderness than to create it.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold thus rejected the utilitarianism of conservationists such as Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] By the 1930s, Leopold had become one of the first Americans to publish extensively on the startup discipline of wildlife management.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He advocated the scientific management of wildlife habitats by both public and private landholders rather than a reliance on game refuges, hunting laws, and other methods intended to protect specific species of desired game.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The concept of "wilderness" also took on a new meaning; Leopold no longer saw it as a hunting or recreational ground, but as an arena for a healthy biotic community, including wolves and mountain lions.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In 1935, he helped found the Wilderness Society, dedicated to expanding and protecting the nation's wilderness areas.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He regarded the society as "one of the focal points of a new attitude—an intelligent humility toward Man's place in nature." Science writer Connie Barlow says Leopold wrote eloquently from a perspective that today would be called Religious Naturalism.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Though often forgotten, thinking about population dynamics and consumption also shaped Leopold's ecological vision in profound ways.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] By studying wildlife population fluctuations, Leopold extended many of the ideas about carrying capacity and environmental degradation that Raymond Pearl and Edward Murray East had articulated, and these ideas, in turn, shaped his path-breaking ideas of ecological interconnection.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Moreover, although later readers associate Leopold with wildlife ecology, his career helps show how Malthusian ideas of human society intertwined and overlapped with ideas of nature.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He was greatly influenced by ecologists who themselves gleaned ideas from Malthusian models of human society, and himself often thought of human events—especially the Great Depression and World War II—in terms of the models of population and consumption that he was developing for animals.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] One of the most influential books for Leopold during that period was *Our Vanishing Wildlife* by William Temple Hornaday.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] As one of the earliest works dedicated entirely to the threats facing wild game populations this book significantly shaped Leopold's views.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The book sharpened his focus on the importance of game protection, a concern that would remain central to his thinking for many years to come.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold's nature writing is notable for its simple directness.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] His portrayals of various natural environments through which he had moved, or had known for many years, displayed impressive intimacy with what exists and happens in nature.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] This includes detailed diaries and journals of his Forest Service activity, hunting and field experience, as well as observations and activities at his Sand County farm.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He offered frank criticism of the harm he believed was frequently done to natural systems (such as land) out of a sense of a culture or society's sovereign ownership over the land base – eclipsing any sense of a community of life to which humans belong.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The book was published in 1949, shortly after Leopold's death.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] It was structured in a series of monthly essays where he went in depth about land ethics and nature.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Several of these monthly essays were accompanied with sketches from the different landscapes and plants he found.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Additionally, he would have philosophical segments that would contribute to his land ethic concepts.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Thinking Like a Mountain was originally written during World War II and shows that Leopold's thinking was shaped by that global cataclysm.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In "The Land Ethic", a chapter in *A Sand County Almanac*, Leopold delves into conservation in "The Ecological Conscience" section.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He wrote: "Conservation is a state of harmony between men and land." He noted that conservation guidelines at the time boiled down to: "obey the law, vote right, join some organizations, and practice what conservation is profitable on your own land; the government will do the rest." (p.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold's contributions to conservation, particularly his role in establishing the Gila Wilderness Area, are deeply intertwined with the evolution of his philosophical views.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In the early 20th century, Leopold's work with the U.S.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Forest Service in the American Southwest was grounded in the agency's utilitarian ethos, which prioritized resource extraction and economic productivity.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] As a forester in Arizona and New Mexico, Leopold initially approached wildlife management with a focus on maximizing game species for human benefit, a perspective aligned with the Progressive Era's emphasis on efficient resource use.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold's philosophy began to evolve in the 1910s and 1920s, driven by field observations, ecological consequences of his early practices, and intellectual growth.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] A pivotal moment in Leopold's transformation occurred around 1909–1910, during his early years in the Apache National Forest.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In his essay “Thinking Like a Mountain”, Leopold recounts shooting a wolf and watching it die, observing “a fierce green fire” in its eyes.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] This visceral experience, coupled with witnessing the subsequent ecological fallout, profoundly altered his perspective.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The incident highlighted the role of predators in maintaining ecological balance.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Without wolves, deer populations surged, overgrazing vegetation and triggering a cascade of environmental damage, including soil erosion and loss of biodiversity.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold realized that “the mountain” required all its components—predators, prey, and plants—to function healthily.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] This moment marked a shift from viewing wildlife in isolation to understanding ecosystems as dynamic, interdependent systems.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] It planted the seed for his later ecocentric philosophy, where no single species, including humans, could be prioritized at the expense of the whole.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In "Marshland Elegy", an excerpt from *A Sand County Almanac,* Leopold describes the process of destruction for American marshland as well as the efforts to reinvigorate those marshlands after that destruction.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold speak both to the way in which the halting of farmland development in these areas represents positive change for the cranes and other wildlife that relies on marshes as well as the limitations of the strategies implemented by conservationists in the issue.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold criticized conservation strategy in that to make the public cherish the communities we conserve they need to "see and fondle" them which can make the conservation effort self-defeating.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] At the time this essay was written Sandhill Cranes had dwindled to merely 25 breeding pairs in Wisconsin, luckily since then the crane population has recovered with the midwest now being home to over 15,000 sandhill cranes.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] These efforts were inspired by this essay and carried out by the Aldo Leopold foundation.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] These efforts give a positive example to be looked to for future conservation efforts.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Game Management is deemed Leopold's most important work as it founded a new science by combining the likes of agriculture, biology, ecology, and other sciences.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] This book brought about a revolution within conservation and placed Leopold as the founder of the Department of Game Management at The University of Wisconsin.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] For more than 40 years after its publication, it was the leading textbook in the field of wildlife management.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Published nearly 45 years after the death of Leopold, The River of the Mother of God, includes 59 essays drawn from Leopold's unpublished manuscripts found at The University of Wisconsin and Leopold's overlooked published work.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] This collection is titled after one of Leopold's most popular essays from 1924, “The River of the Mother of God,” but it spans Leopold's life discussing themes of wilderness preservation, ecology, agriculture, land ethics, and natural esthetics from his teenage years until his last years.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] This work dives into a deeper view of Leopold and shows the lasting impact he made on the field of conservation.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In *A Sand County Almanac*, Aldo Leopold's essay “A Man’s Leisure Time” provides us with a thoughtful examination of how leisure enriches our lives by deepening our connection with nature.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold believed that how one spends their free time is a good indicator of one's intelligence and character.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold states, “How miserable are the idle hours of the ignorant man!” contributing to his idea that leisure time is meaningful and it is important to take in the nature around when present with the opportunity.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] According to Leopold, leisure activities should not be relaxing time but ways to achieve personal growth and understanding.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He describes hobbies as "a defiance of the contemporary," suggesting that they allow individuals to step away from the relentless pace of modern life and engage in activities that are rewarding and enriching.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold highlights that such pursuits, whether it's collecting fossils or cultivating a garden, can lead to a profound appreciation of the land and how important and amazing nature is.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In this chapter, Mr.Leopold encourages the reader to consider what they do with their free or leisure time in their life.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold advocates for activities that promote a deeper understanding of the natural world.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In 1933, Aldo Leopold became Professor of Game Management at the University of Wisconsin-Madison, the first position of its kind in the country.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Through his contributions to and knowledge of the field, he developed curricula and ran the program, which was eventually redubbed Wildlife Ecology.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] "Game Management" during this time meant the scientific study and the practical application of techniques for maintaining a healthy wildlife population, especially those that are hunted for sport.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Through his expertise, the area of wildlife management grew from just managing populations within life to a larger egocialcal approach to managing wildlife population.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Game management was a branch of conservation biology to Aldo Leopold.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He was concerned about the whole ecological balance of the environment and not just one species.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He created a field that was hit every area ecology, policy, forestry, and ethics.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He even published a textbook for his class titles "Game management", also published in 1933.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In 1950 The Wildlife Society honored Leopold by creating an annual award in his name.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Furthermore, the foundation formed a Leopold Conservation Award to recognize farmers, forestland owners, and private land owners for inspirational conservation efforts and leadership within land ethics.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The *Aldo Leopold Foundation* of Baraboo, Wisconsin, was founded in 1982 by Aldo and Estella Leopold's five children as a 501(c)3 not-for-profit conservation organization whose mission is "to foster the land ethic through the legacy of Aldo Leopold".
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Foundation owns and manages the original Aldo Leopold Shack and Farm and 300 surrounding acres, in addition to several other parcels.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Its headquarters is the green-built *Leopold Center* where it conducts educational and land stewardship programs.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The foundation also acts as the executor of Leopold's literary estate, encourages scholarship on Leopold, and serves as a clearinghouse for information regarding Leopold, his work, and his ideas.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] It provides interpretive resources and tours for thousands of visitors annually, distributes a curriculum about how to use Leopold's writing and ideas in environmental education.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The center maintains a robust website and numerous print resources.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In 2012, in collaboration with the United States Forest Service, the foundation and the Center for Humans and Nature released the first full-length film about Leopold, titled *Green Fire: Aldo Leopold and a Land Ethic for Our Time*.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The film aired on public television stations across the nation and won a Midwest regional Emmy award in the documentary category.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Wilderness in New Mexico's Gila National Forest was named after him in 1980.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Center for Sustainable Agriculture was established in 1987 at Iowa State University in Ames.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Since its founding, it has pioneered new forms of sustainable agriculture practices.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Forest Service established the Aldo Leopold Wilderness Research Institute at the University of Montana, Missoula in 1993.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Neighborhood Historic District, which includes Leopold's former home in Albuquerque, New Mexico, was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2002.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Legacy Trail System, a system of 42 state trails in Wisconsin, was created by the state in 2007 to honor Leopold's contributions to the conservation and outdoor recreation.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] This trail covers more than 1,700 miles across the state of Wisconsin.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Many of the trails pass through forests, scenics natural areas, and state parks.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] There are signs, along the trails, to showcase information about Leopold's life, his conservation work, and natural information about the surrounding area.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Center for Sustainable Agriculture in Iowa, created through the 1987 Iowa Groundwater Protection Act is committed to "new ways to farm profitably while conserving natural resources as well as reducing negative environmental and social impacts".
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] An organization, the Leopold Heritage Group, is "dedicated to promoting the global legacy of Aldo Leopold in his hometown of Burlington, Iowa." This groups preserves and shares Leopold's legacy by providing local events, educational programs, and conservation projects.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The "Leopold Heritage Group", supports efforts to maintain Leopold-relates sites around the area for example, his childhood home and many places that he has explored as a child.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] In 1985, Leopold was inducted along with John Muir, a naturalist and preservationist, as the first inductees to the Wisconsin Conservation Hall of Fame.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The Hall of Fame is located in Stevens Point, Wisconsin, it was created to recognize the individuals who have made important contributions to conserving the natural state of resources around the state.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Residence Hall at the University of Wisconsin-Madison was named after him.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Leopold's Preserve in Haymarket, Virginia was established in 2014.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] This preserve is a 380-acre park that is committed to preserving diverse ecosystems, natural scenes, and protecting threatened land from industrial and commercial development.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold is well known for being the founder of wildlife management, he played a key role in establishing ethics in the wildlife world.
[src:land-ethic/aldo-leopold] He was a driving force behind the creation of the Gila National Forest Wilderness, and his legacy lives on today as the Gila National Forest has been standing strong since 1924, when the National Forest was created.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Anthropocentrism tends to interpret the world in terms of human values and experiences.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] It is considered to be profoundly embedded in many modern human cultures and conscious acts.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] It is a major concept in the field of environmental ethics and environmental philosophy, where it is often considered to be the root cause of problems created by human action within the ecosphere.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] However, many proponents of anthropocentrism state that this is not necessarily the case: they argue that a sound long-term view acknowledges that the global environment must be made continually suitable for humans and that the real issue is shallow anthropocentrism.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Some environmental philosophers have argued that anthropocentrism is a core part of a perceived human drive to dominate or "master" the Earth.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Anthropocentrism is believed by some to be the central problematic concept in environmental philosophy, where it is used to draw attention to claims of a systematic bias in traditional Western attitudes to the non-human world that shapes humans' sense of self and identities.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Val Plumwood argued that anthropocentrism plays an analogous role in green theory to androcentrism in feminist theory and ethnocentrism in anti-racist theory.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Plumwood called human-centredness "anthrocentrism" to emphasise this parallel.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] One of the first extended philosophical essays addressing environmental ethics, John Passmore's *Man's Responsibility for Nature*, has been criticised by defenders of deep ecology because of its anthropocentrism, often claimed to be constitutive of traditional Western moral thought.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Indeed, defenders of anthropocentrism concerned with the ecological crisis contend that the maintenance of a healthy, sustainable environment is necessary for human well-being as opposed to for its own sake.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] According to William Grey, the problem with a "shallow" viewpoint is not that it is human-centred: "What's wrong with shallow views is not their concern about the well-being of humans, but that they do not really consider enough in what that well-being consists.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Many devoted environmentalists encompass a somewhat anthropocentric-based philosophical view supporting the fact that they will argue in favor of saving the environment for the sake of human populations.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Grey writes: "We should be concerned to promote a rich, diverse, and vibrant biosphere.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Conversely, anthropocentric thinking can also lead people to underattribute human characteristics to other organisms.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] For instance, it may be tempting to wrongly assume that an animal that is very different from humans, such as an insect, will not share particular biological characteristics, such as reproduction or blood circulation.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Anthropocentric thinking has predominantly been studied in young children (mostly up to the age of 10) by developmental psychologists interested in its relevance to biology education.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Children as young as 6 have been found to attribute human characteristics to species unfamiliar to them (in Japan), such as rabbits, grasshoppers or tulips.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Although relatively little is known about its persistence at a later age, evidence exists that this pattern of human exceptionalist thinking can continue through young adulthood at least, even among students who have been increasingly educated in biology.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] The notion that anthropocentric thinking is an innate human characteristic has been challenged by study of American children raised in urban environments, among whom it appears to emerge between the ages of 3 and 5 years as an acquired perspective.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Children's recourse to anthropocentric thinking seems to vary with their experience of nature, and cultural assumptions about the place of humans in the natural world.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] For example, whereas young children who kept goldfish were found to think of frogs as being more goldfish-like, other children tended to think of frogs in terms of humans.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] More generally, children raised in rural environments appear to use anthropocentric thinking less than their urban counterparts because of their greater familiarity with different species of animals and plants.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Studies involving children from some of the indigenous peoples of the Americas have found little use of anthropocentric thinking.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] In the 1985 CBC series "A Planet For the Taking", David Suzuki explored the Old Testament roots of anthropocentrism and how it shaped human views of non-human animals.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] The use of the word "dominion" in the *Genesis* has been used to justify an anthropocentric worldview, but recently some have found it controversial, viewing it as possibly a mistranslation from the Hebrew.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] However an argument can be made that the Bible actually places all the importance on God as creator, and humans as merely another part of creation.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Moses Maimonides, a Torah scholar who lived in the twelfth century AD, was renowned for his staunch opposition to anthropocentrism.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] He referred to humans as "just a drop in the bucket" and asserted that "humans are not the axis of the world".
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] He also claimed that anthropocentric thinking is what leads humans to believe in the existence of evil things in nature.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] According to Rabbi Norman Lamm, Moses Maimonides "refuted the exaggerated ideas about the importance of man and urged us to abandon these fantasies.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Catholic social teaching sees the pre-eminence of human beings over the rest of creation in terms of service rather than domination.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] In his follow-up exhortation, *Laudate Deum* (2023) he refers to a preferable understanding of "the unique and central value of the human being amid the marvellous concert of all God's creatures" as a "situated anthropocentrism".
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Anthropocentrism is the grounding for some naturalistic concepts of specifically *human* rights as opposed to animal rights extended to include the human species.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Apologists of anthropocentrism argue that it is the necessary fundamental premise to defend universal human rights, since what matters morally is simply being human.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] For example, noted philosopher Mortimer J.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Author and anthropocentrism apologist Wesley J.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Smith from the Discovery Institute has written that human exceptionalism is what gives rise to human duties to each other, the natural world, and to treat animals humanely.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Anthropocentrism is closely related to the notion of speciesism, defined by Richard D.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Ryder as a "a prejudice or attitude of bias in favour of the interests of members of one's own species and against those of members of other species".
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] One of the earliest critics of anthropocentrism was Edward Payson Evans in his book *Evolutional Ethics and Animal Psychology* (1897), where he challenges the idea that humans are fundamentally distinct from other sentient beings.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] He argues that anthropocentric psychology and ethics persist, treating humans as superior and denying mental or moral connections to other species.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Evans suggests these beliefs stem from human self-importance, which overlooks the shared qualities of sentience across species and questions the ethical implications of such a view.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Howard Moore, in *The Universal Kinship* (1906), expanded on this critique, asserting that Charles Darwin's *On the Origin of Species* (1859) "sealed the doom" of anthropocentrism.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Moore argued that the doctrine of organic evolution, which established the common genesis of all animals, fundamentally altered humanity's view of its place in the natural world.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Before the publication of *The Origin of Species*, humans may have been seen as distinct from other creatures, but with the advent of evolutionary theory, all species were recognized as sharing a common ancestry.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Moore considered this shift one of the most significant intellectual developments, comparable to the groundbreaking insights of Galileo and Copernicus.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] While humans cognition is relatively advanced, many traits traditionally used to justify humanity exceptionalism (such as rationality, emotional complexity and social bonds) are not unique to humans.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Research in ethology has shown that non-human animals, such as primates, elephants, and cetaceans, also demonstrate complex social structures, emotional depth, and problem-solving abilities.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] This challenges the claim that humans possess qualities absent in other animals, and which would justify denying moral status to them.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Animal welfare proponents attribute moral consideration to all sentient animals, proportional to their ability to have positive or negative mental experiences.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] It is notably associated with the ethical theory of utilitarianism, which aims to maximize well-being.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] According to David Pearce, "other things being equal, equally strong interests should count equally." Jeremy Bentham is also known for raising early the issue of animal welfare, arguing that "the question is not, Can they reason? nor, Can they talk? but, Can they suffer?".
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Animal welfare proponents can in theory accept animal exploitation if the benefits outweigh the harms.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] But in practice, they generally consider that intensive animal farming causes a massive amount of suffering that outweighs the relatively minor benefit that humans get from consuming animals.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Animal rights proponents argue that all animals have inherent rights, similar to human rights, and should not be used as means to human ends.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Unlike animal welfare advocates, who focus on minimizing suffering, animal rights supporters often call for the total abolition of practices that exploit animals, such as intensive animal farming, animal testing, and hunting.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Prominent figures like Tom Regan argue that animals are "subjects of a life" with inherent value, deserving moral consideration regardless of the potential benefits humans may derive from using them.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] In fiction from all eras and societies, there is fiction depicting the actions of humans to ride, eat, milk, and otherwise treat (non-human) animals as inferior.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] There are occasional fictional exceptions, such as talking animals as aberrations to the rule distinguishing people from animals.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] In science fiction, *humanocentrism* is the idea that humans, as both beings and as a species, are the superior sentients.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Essentially the equivalent of racial supremacy on a galactic scale, it entails intolerant discrimination against sentient non-humans, much like race supremacists discriminate against those not of their race.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] A prime example of this concept is utilized as a story element for the *Mass Effect* series.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] After humanity's first contact results in a brief war, many humans in the series develop suspicious or even hostile attitudes towards the game's various alien races.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] By the time of the first game, which takes place several decades after the war, many humans still retain such sentiments in addition to forming 'pro-human' organizations.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] This idea is countered by anti-humanism.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] At times, this ideal also includes fear of and superiority over strong AIs and cyborgs, downplaying the ideas of integration, cybernetic revolts, machine rule and Tilden's Laws of Robotics.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Mark Twain mocked the belief in human supremacy in *Letters from the Earth* (written c.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] The *Planet of the Apes* franchise focuses on the analogy of apes becoming the dominant species in society and the fall of humans (see also human extinction).
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] In the 1968 film, Taylor, a human states "take your stinking paws off me, you damn dirty ape!".
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] In the 2001 film, this is contrasted with Attar (a gorilla)'s quote "take your stinking hands off me, you damn dirty human!".
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] This links in with allusions that in becoming the dominant species apes are becoming more like humans (anthropomorphism).
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] In the film *Battle for the Planet of the Apes*, Virgil, an orangutan states "ape has never killed ape, let alone an ape child.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] It was cut with a sword." in reference to planned murder; a stereotypical human concept.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] Additionally, in *Dawn of the Planet of the Apes*, Caesar states "I always think...ape better than human.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] In George Orwell's novel *Animal Farm*, this theme of anthropocentrism is also present.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] The 2012 documentary *The Superior Human?* systematically analyzes anthropocentrism and concludes that value is fundamentally an opinion, and since life forms naturally value their own traits, most humans are misled to believe that they are actually more valuable than other species.
[src:land-ethic/anthropocentrism] This natural bias, according to the film, combined with a received sense of comfort and an excuse for exploitation of non-humans cause anthropocentrism to remain in society.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Kingsolver has received numerous awards, including the Dayton Literary Peace Prize's Richard C.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Holbrooke Distinguished Achievement Award in 2011 and the National Humanities Medal.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] After winning for *The Lacuna* in 2010 and *Demon Copperhead* in 2023, Kingsolver became the first author to win the Women's Prize for Fiction twice.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Since 1993, each one of her book titles have been on the *New York Times* Best Seller list.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Kingsolver was raised in rural Kentucky, lived briefly in the Congo in her early childhood, and currently lives in Virginia, in the Appalachia region.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Kingsolver earned degrees in biology, ecology, and evolutionary biology at DePauw University and the University of Arizona, and worked as a freelance writer before she began writing novels.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] In 2000, the politically progressive Kingsolver established the Bellwether Prize to support "literature of social change".
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Kingsolver was born in 1955 in Annapolis, Maryland, the daughter of Wendell Roy Kingsolver and Virginia Lee (née Henry) Kingsolver, but grew up in Carlisle, Kentucky.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] When Kingsolver was seven, her father, a physician, took the family to Léopoldville, Congo (now Kinshasa, Democratic Republic of the Congo).
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] After graduating from high school, Kingsolver attended DePauw University in Greencastle, Indiana, on a music scholarship, studying classical piano.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] She changed her major to biology after realizing that "classical pianists compete for six job openings a year, and the rest of [them] get to play 'Blue Moon' in a hotel lobby".
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Kingsolver was involved in activism on her campus, and took part in protests against the Vietnam War.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] In 1977, Kingsolver graduated Phi Beta Kappa with a Bachelor of Science, and moved to France for a year.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] In 1980, she enrolled in graduate school at the University of Arizona, where she earned a master's degree in ecology and evolutionary biology.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] In 1985, Kingsolver married Joseph Hoffmann, and gave birth to their daughter Camille in 1987.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] During the first First Gulf War, she moved with her daughter to Tenerife in the Canary Islands for a year, mostly due to her frustration over America's military involvement.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] After returning to the United States in 1992, she separated from her husband.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] In 1994, Kingsolver was awarded an honorary Doctorate of Letters from her alma mater, DePauw University.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] That same year, she married Steven Lee Hopp, an ornithologist, and their daughter Lily was born in 1996.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] In 2004, Kingsolver moved with her family to a farm in Washington County, Virginia.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] In 2008, she received an honorary Doctorate of Humane Letters from Duke University, where she delivered a commencement address entitled "How to Be Hopeful".
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] In the late 1990s, Kingsolver was a founding member of the Rock Bottom Remainders, a rock-and-roll band made up of published writers.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Other band members included Amy Tan, Matt Groening, Dave Barry, and Stephen King, and they played for one week during the year.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Kingsolver played the keyboard, but is no longer an active member of the band.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] In a 2010 interview with *The Guardian*, Kingsolver said, "I never wanted to be famous, and still don't… the universe rewarded me with what I dreaded most".
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] She said she created her own website just to compete with a plethora of fake ones "as a defense to protect my family from misinformation".
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Kingsolver lives in the Appalachia area of the United States.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] She said in 2020 that rural America is generally regarded by artistic elites with "a profound antipathy".
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Kingsolver began her full-time writing career in the mid-1980s as a science writer for the University of Arizona, which eventually led to freelance feature writing, including many cover stories for the local alternative weekly, the *Tucson Weekly*.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] She began her career in fiction writing after winning a short-story contest in a local Phoenix newspaper.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Kingsolver's first novel, *The Bean Trees*, was published in 1988, and told the story of a young woman who leaves Kentucky for Arizona, adopting an abandoned child along the way; she wrote it at night while pregnant with her first child and struggling with insomnia.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Her next work of fiction, published in 1990, was *Homeland and Other Stories*, a collection of short stories on a variety of topics exploring various themes from the evolution of cultural and ancestral lands to the struggles of marriage.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] The novel *Animal Dreams* was also published in 1990, followed by *Pigs in Heaven*, the sequel to *The Bean Trees*, in 1993.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Every book that Kingsolver has written since *Pigs in Heaven* has been on *The New York Times* Best Seller list.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Her next novel, published in 2000, was *Prodigal Summer*, set in southern Appalachia.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] In 2000, she was awarded the National Humanities Medal by the U.S.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Kingsolver wrote a *Los Angeles Times* opinion piece following the U.S. bombing of Afghanistan in the wake of the September 11 attacks, which received widespread criticism for conflating innocent Afghans with the Taliban regime.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] She wrote, "I feel like I'm standing on a playground where the little boys are all screaming at each other, 'He started it!' and throwing rocks that keep taking out another eye, another tooth.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] I keep looking around for somebody's mother to come on the scene saying, 'Boys!
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Who started it cannot possibly be the issue here.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] People are getting hurt.'" By some accounts, she was "denounced as a traitor," but rebounded from these accusations and later wrote about them.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Starting in April 2005, Kingsolver and her family spent a year making every effort to eat food produced as locally as possible.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Living on their farm in rural Virginia, they grew much of their own food and obtained most of the rest from their neighbors and other local farmers.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Kingsolver, her husband, and her elder daughter chronicled their experiences of that year in the book *Animal, Vegetable, Miracle: A Year of Food Life*, published in 2007.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Although exceptions were made for staple ingredients not available locally, such as coffee and olive oil, the family grew vegetables, raised livestock, made cheese, and preserved much of their harvest.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] *Animal, Vegetable, Miracle* won the 2008 James Beard Foundation Award.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Kingsolver returned to novel-writing with *The Lacuna*, published in 2009.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Kingsolver received her first Women's Prize for Fiction for the novel in 2010.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] *The Lacuna* won the 2010 Orange Prize for Fiction.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] *Flight Behavior* was published in 2012.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] It explores environmental themes and highlights the potential effects of global warming on the monarch butterfly.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] In 2011, Kingsolver was the first ever recipient of the Dayton Literary Peace Prize Richard C.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Holbrooke Distinguished Achievement Award.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] The newly named award to celebrate the U.S. diplomat who played an instrumental role in negotiating the Dayton Peace Accords in 1995.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] In 2014, Kingsolver was awarded the Lifetime Achievement Award by the Library of Virginia.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] The award recognizes outstanding and long-lasting contributions to literature by a Virginian.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] In 2018 the Library of Virginia named her one of the Virginia Women in History.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Kingsolver is also a published poet and essayist.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Two of her essay collections, *High Tide in Tucson* (1995) and *Small Wonder* (2003), have been published, and an anthology of her poetry was published in 1998 under the title *Another America*.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] A second collection of poetry, entitled *How to Fly (In Ten Thousand Easy Lessons)* was published in 2020.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Her essay "Where to Begin" appears in the anthology *Knitting Yarns: Writers on Knitting*(2013), published by W.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Her prose poetry also accompanied photographs by Annie Griffiths Belt in a 2002 work titled *Last Stand: America's Virgin Lands*.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Her major nonfiction works include her 1990 publication *Holding the Line: Women in the Great Arizona Mine Strike of 1983* and 2007's *Animal, Vegetable, Miracle*, a description of eating locally.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] She has also been published as a science journalist in periodicals such as *Economic Botany* on topics such as desert plants and bioresources.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] In 2000, Kingsolver established the Bellwether Prize for Fiction.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Named for the bellwether, the literary prize supports writers whose works support positive social change.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] The award is given to a U.S. citizen for a previously unpublished work of fiction that addresses issues of social justice.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] The Bellwether Prize is awarded in even-numbered years and includes guaranteed major publication and a cash prize of US$25,000, fully funded by Kingsolver.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] She has stated that she wanted to create a literary prize to "encourage writers, publishers, and readers to consider how fiction engages visions of social change and human justice".
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] In May 2011, the PEN American Center announced it would take over administration of the prize, to be known as the PEN/Bellwether Prize for Socially Engaged Fiction.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Kingsolver has written novels in both the first-person and third-person narrative styles, and she frequently employs overlapping narratives.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Kingsolver often writes about places and situations with which she is familiar; many of her stories are based in places she has lived, such as Central Africa, Arizona, and Appalachia.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] She has stated that her novels are not autobiographical, although there are often commonalities between her life and her work.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Her work is often strongly idealistic and has been called a form of activism.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Her characters are frequently written around struggles for social equality, such as the hardships faced by undocumented immigrants, the working poor, and single mothers.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Other common themes in her work include the balancing of individuality with the desire to live in a community, and the interaction and conflict between humans and the ecosystems in which they live.
[src:land-ethic/barbara-kingsolver] Kingsolver has been said to use prose and engaging narratives to make historical events, such as the Congo's struggles for independence, more interesting and engaging for the average reader.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Advocates of biocentrism often promote the preservation of biodiversity, animal rights, and environmental protection.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The term has also been employed by advocates of "left biocentrism", which combines deep ecology with an "anti-industrial and anti-capitalist" position (according to David Orton *et al.*).
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] In the simplest of terms as well as form, biocentrism is the belief that all living organisms, without exception, individually possess equal value and the same exact right to live, requiring identical moral treatment, regard, and prioritization.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Usually, the term biocentrism encompasses all environmental ethics that "extend the status of moral object from human beings to all living things in nature".
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Biocentric ethics calls for a rethinking of the relationship between humans and nature.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Biocentrists observe that all species have inherent value, and that humans are not "superior" to other species in a moral or ethical sense.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] All species are part of a system of interdependence.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] All living organisms pursue their own "good" in their own ways.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Human beings are not inherently superior to other living things.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The most important of these four main pillars is likely the idea that human beings are not inherently superior to other living things.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] People have divergent views on many specific aspects of almost everything.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Not all biocentrists even subscribe to the abstract concept of value, which is why heavy emphasis is placed on the fourth pillar.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Biocentrism views individual species as parts of the living biosphere.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] It observes the consequences of reducing biodiversity on both small and large scales and points to the inherent value all species have to the environment.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The environment is seen for what it is; the biosphere within which we live and depend on the maintaining of its diversity for our health.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] From these observations the ethical points are raised.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Biocentric ethics differs from classical and traditional ethical thinking.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Rather than focusing on strict moral rules, as in Classical ethics, it focuses on attitudes and character.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] In contrast with traditional ethics, it is nonhierarchical and gives priority to the natural world rather than to humankind exclusively.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Biocentric ethics includes Albert Schweitzer's ethics of "Reverence for Life", Peter Singer's ethics of Animal Liberation and Paul W.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Taylor's ethics of biocentric egalitarianism.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Albert Schweitzer's "reverence for life" principle was a precursor of modern biocentric ethics.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] In contrast with traditional ethics, the ethics of "reverence for life" denies any distinction between "high and low" or "valuable and less valuable" life forms, dismissing such categorization as arbitrary and subjective.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Conventional ethics concerned itself exclusively with human beings—that is to say, morality applied only to interpersonal relationships—whereas Schweitzer's ethical philosophy introduced a "depth, energy, and function that differ[s] from the ethics that merely involved humans".
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] "Reverence for life" was a "new ethics, because it is not only an extension of ethics, but also a transformation of the nature of ethics".
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Similarly, Peter Singer argues that non-human animals deserve the same equality of consideration that we extend to human beings.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Using membership in the species *Homo sapiens* as a criterion of moral importance is completely arbitrary.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Of the remaining criteria we might consider, only sentience is a plausible criterion of moral importance.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Using sentience as a criterion of moral importance entails that we extend the same basic moral consideration (i.e.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] "basic principle of equality") to other sentient creatures that we do to human beings.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Therefore, we ought to extend to animals the same equality of consideration that we extend to human beings.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Singer's work, while notable in the canon of environmental ethics, should not be considered as fully biocentric.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Singer's ethics is extended from humans to nonhuman animals because the criterion for moral inclusion (sentience) is found in both humans and nonhuman animals, thus it would be arbitrary to deny it to nonhuman animals simply because they were not human.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] However, not all biological entities are sentient, consider: algae, plants and trees, fungi, lichens, mollusks, protozoa, for example.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] For an ethical theory to be biocentric, it must have a reason for extending ethical inclusion to the entire biosphere (as in Taylor and Schweitzer).
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The requirement for environmental ethics to move beyond sentience as criteria for inclusion in the moral realm is discussed in Tom Regan's 1981 paper "The Nature and Possibility of an Environmental Ethic".
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Biocentrism is most commonly associated with the work of Paul W.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Taylor, especially his book *Respect for Nature: A Theory of Environmental Ethics* (1986).
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Taylor maintains that biocentrism is an "attitude of respect for nature", whereby one attempts to make an effort to live one's life in a way that respects the welfare and inherent worth of all living creatures.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] This community consists of a system of interdependence between all members, both physically, and in terms of relationships with other species.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Every organism is a "teleological centre of life", that is, each organism has a purpose and a reason for being, which is inherently "good" or "valuable".
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Humans are not inherently superior to other species.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Historian Donald Worster traces today's biocentric philosophies, which he sees as part of a recovery of a sense of kinship between man and nature, to the reaction by the British intelligencia of the Victorian era against the Christian ethic of dominion over nature.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] In 1859, Charles Darwin published his book *On the Origin of Species*.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] This publication sparked the beginning of biocentrist views by introducing evolution and "its removal of humans from their supernatural origins and placement into the framework of natural laws".
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The work of Aldo Leopold has also been associated with biocentrism.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The essay "The Land Ethic" in Leopold's book *Sand County Almanac* (1949) points out that although throughout history women and slaves have been considered property, all people have now been granted rights and freedoms.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Leopold notes that today land is still considered property as people once were.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] He asserts that ethics should be extended to the land as "an evolutionary possibility and an ecological necessity".
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] He argues that while people's instincts encourage them to compete with others, their ethics encourage them to co-operate with others.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] He suggests that "the land ethic simply enlarges the boundaries of the community to include soils, waters, plants, and animals, or collectively: the land".
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] In a sense this attitude would encourage humans to co-operate with the land rather than compete with it.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Outside of formal philosophical works biocentric thought is common among pre-colonial tribal peoples who knew no world other than the natural world.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The paradigm of biocentrism and the values that it promotes are beginning to be used in law.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] In recent years (as of 2011), cities in Maine, Pennsylvania, New Hampshire and Virginia have adopted laws that protect the rights of nature.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The purpose of these laws is to prevent the degradation of nature, especially by corporations who may want to exploit natural resources and land space, and to also use the environment as a dumping ground for toxic waste.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The first country to include rights of nature in its constitution is Ecuador (see 2008 Constitution of Ecuador).
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Article 71 states that nature "has the right to integral respect for its existence and for the maintenance and regeneration of its life cycles, structure, functions and evolutionary processes".
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] In Islam, biocentric ethics stem from the belief that all of creation belongs to Allah (God), not humans, and to assume that non-human animals and plants exist merely to benefit humankind leads to environmental destruction and misuse.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] As all living organisms exist to praise God, human destruction of other living things prevents the earth's natural and subtle means of praising God.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The Qur'an acknowledges that humans are not the only all-important creatures and emphasizes a respect for nature.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Hinduism contains many elements of biocentrism.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] In Hinduism, humans have no special authority over other creatures, and all living things have souls ('atman').
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Brahman (God) is the "efficient cause" and Prakrti (nature), is the "material cause" of the universe.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] However, while Hinduism does not give the same direct authority over nature that the Judeo-Christian-Islamic god grants, they are subject to a "higher and more authoritative responsibility for creation".
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The most important aspect of this is the doctrine of Ahimsa (non-violence).
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The Yājñavalkya Smṛti warns, "the wicked person who kills animals which are protected has to live in hell fire for the days equal to the number of hairs on the body of that animal".
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The essential aspect of this doctrine is the belief that the Supreme Being incarnates into the forms of various species.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The Hindu belief in Saṃsāra (the cycle of life, death and rebirth) encompasses reincarnation into non-human forms.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] It is believed that one lives 8,400,000 lifetimes before one becomes a human.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Each species is in this process of samsara until one attains moksha (liberation).
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Another doctrinal source for the equal treatment of all life is found in the Rigveda.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The Rigveda states that trees and plants possess divine healing properties.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] It is still popularly believed that every tree has a Vriksa-devata (a tree deity).
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Trees are ritually worshiped through prayer, offerings, and the sacred thread ceremony.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The Vriksa-devata worshiped as manifestations of the Divine.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Tree planting is considered a religious duty.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The Jaina tradition exists in tandem with Hinduism and shares many of its biocentric elements.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Ahimsa (non-violence), the central teaching of Jainism, means more than not hurting other humans.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] It means intending not to cause physical, mental or spiritual harm to any part of nature.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] In the words of Mahavira: 'You are that which you wish to harm.' Compassion is a pillar of non-violence.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Jainism encourages people to practice an attitude of compassion towards all life.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The principle of interdependence is also very important in Jainism.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] This states that all of nature is bound together, and that "if one does not care for nature one does not care for oneself.".
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Another essential Jain teaching is self-restraint.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Jainism discourages wasting the gifts of nature, and encourages its practitioners to reduce their needs as far as possible.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] The Buddha's teachings encourage people "to live simply, to cherish tranquility, to appreciate the natural cycle of life".
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Buddhism emphasizes that everything in the universe affects everything else.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] "Nature is an ecosystem in which trees affect climate, the soil, and the animals, just as the climate affects the trees, the soil, the animals and so on.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Although this holistic approach is more ecocentric than biocentric, it is also biocentric, as it maintains that all living things are important and that humans are not above other creatures or nature.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Within the Catholic tradition of Christian thought, Pope Benedict XVI noted that "the Church’s magisterium expresses grave misgivings about notions of the environment inspired by ecocentrism and biocentrism".
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] This, he stated, was because "such notions eliminate the difference of identity and worth between the human person and other living things.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Biocentrism has faced criticism for a number of reasons.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Some of this criticism grows out of the concern that biocentrism is an anti-human paradigm and that it will not hesitate to sacrifice human well-being for the greater good.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Biocentrism has also been criticized for its individualism; emphasizing too much on the importance of individual life and neglecting the importance of collective groups, such as an ecosystem.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] A more complex form of criticism focuses on the contradictions of biocentrism.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Opposed to anthropocentrism, which sees humans as having a higher status than other species, biocentrism puts humans on a par with the rest of nature, and not above it.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] In his essay *A Critique of Anti-Anthropocentric Biocentrism* Richard Watson suggests that if this is the case, then "Human ways—human culture—and human actions are as natural as the ways in which any other species of animals behaves".
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] He goes on to suggest that if humans must change their behavior to refrain from disturbing and damaging the natural environment, then that results in setting humans apart from other species and assigning more power to them (to human beings).
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] This then takes us back to the basic beliefs of anthropocentrism.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Watson also claims that the extinction of species is "Nature's way" and that if humans were to instigate their own self-destruction by exploiting the rest of nature, then so be it.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] Therefore, he suggests that the real reason humans should reduce their destructive behavior in relation to other species is not because we are equals but because the destruction of other species will also result in our own destruction.
[src:land-ethic/biocentrism-ethics] This view also brings us back to an anthropocentric perspective.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] tape (right) with the hook and loop design.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The Theory of Evolution is a feature of biological systems for over 3.8 billion years according to observed life appearance estimations.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Theoretically evolving species with high performance using commonly found materials.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Surfaces of solids interact with other surfaces and the environment and derive the properties of materials.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Biological materials are highly organized from the molecular to the nano-, micro-, and macroscales, often in a hierarchical manner with intricate nanoarchitecture that ultimately makes up a myriad of different functional elements.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Properties of materials and surfaces result from a complex interplay between surface structure and morphology and physical and chemical properties.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Many materials, surfaces, and objects in general provide multifunctionality.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Various materials, structures, and devices have been fabricated for commercial interest by engineers, material scientists, chemists, and biologists, and for beauty, structure, and design by artists and architects.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Nature has solved engineering problems such as self-healing abilities, environmental exposure tolerance and resistance, hydrophobicity, self-assembly, and harnessing solar energy.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Economic impact of bioinspired materials and surfaces is significant, on the order of several hundred billion dollars per year worldwide.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] One of the early examples of biomimicry was the study of birds and bats to enable human flight.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Although never successful in creating a "flying machine", Leonardo da Vinci (1452–1519) was a keen observer of the anatomy and flight of aves and mammals, and made numerous notes and sketches on his observations as well as sketches of "flying machines".
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The Wright Brothers, who succeeded in flying the first heavier-than-air aircraft in 1903, allegedly derived inspiration from observations of pigeons in flight.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] During the 1950s, the American biophysicist and polymath Otto Schmitt developed the concept of "biomimetics".
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] During his doctoral research, he developed the Schmitt trigger by studying the nerves in squid, attempting to engineer a device that replicated the biological system of nerve propagation.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] He continued to focus on devices that mimic natural systems and by 1957 he had perceived a converse to the standard view of biophysics at that time, a view he would come to call biomimetics.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Steele coined a similar term, *bionics*, at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base in Dayton, Ohio, where Otto Schmitt also worked.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Steele defined bionics as "the science of systems which have some function copied from nature, or which represent characteristics of natural systems or their analogues".
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] In 1969, Schmitt used the term "biomimetic" in the title one of his papers, and by 1974 it had found its way into *Webster's Dictionary*.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Bionics entered the same dictionary earlier in 1960 as "a science concerned with the application of data about the functioning of biological systems to the solution of engineering problems".
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Bionic took on a different connotation when Martin Caidin referenced Jack Steele and his work in the novel *Cyborg*, which later resulted in the 1974 television series *The Six Million Dollar Man* and its spin-offs.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The term bionic then became associated with "the use of electronically operated artificial body parts" and "having ordinary human powers increased by or as if by the aid of such devices".
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Because the term *bionic* took on the implication of supernatural strength, the scientific community in English speaking countries largely abandoned it.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The term *biomimicry* appeared as early as 1982.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Biomimicry was popularized by scientist and author Janine Benyus in her 1997 book *Biomimicry: Innovation Inspired by Nature*.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Biomimicry is defined in the book as a "new science that studies nature's models and then imitates or takes inspiration from these designs and processes to solve human problems".
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Benyus suggests looking to Nature as a "Model, Measure, and Mentor" and emphasizes sustainability as an objective of biomimicry.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The potential long-term impacts of biomimicry were quantified in a 2013 Fermanian Business & Economic Institute Report commissioned by the San Diego Zoo.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The findings demonstrated the potential economic and environmental benefits of biomimicry, which can be further seen in Johannes-Paul Fladerer and Ernst Kurzmann's "managemANT" approach.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] This term (a combination of the words "management" and "ant"), describes the usage of behavioural strategies of ants in economic and management strategies.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Biomimetics could in principle be applied in many fields.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Because of the diversity and complexity of biological systems, the number of features that might be imitated is large.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Biomimetic applications are at various stages of development from technologies that might become commercially usable to prototypes.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Murray's law, which in conventional form determined the optimum diameter of blood vessels, has been re-derived to provide simple equations for the pipe or tube diameter which gives a minimum mass engineering system.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Aircraft wing design and flight techniques are being inspired by birds and bats.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The aerodynamics of streamlined design of improved Japanese high speed train Shinkansen 500 Series were modelled after the beak of Kingfisher bird.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] BFRs take inspiration from flying mammals, birds, or insects.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] BFRs can have flapping wings, which generate the lift and thrust, or they can be propeller actuated.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] BFRs with flapping wings have increased stroke efficiencies, increased maneuverability, and reduced energy consumption in comparison to propeller actuated BFRs.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Mammal and bird inspired BFRs share similar flight characteristics and design considerations.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] For instance, both mammal and bird inspired BFRs minimize edge fluttering and pressure-induced wingtip curl by increasing the rigidity of the wing edge and wingtips.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Mammal and insect inspired BFRs can be impact resistant, making them useful in cluttered environments.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Mammal inspired BFRs typically take inspiration from bats, but the flying squirrel has also inspired a prototype.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Examples of bat inspired BFRs include Bat Bot and the DALER.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Mammal inspired BFRs can be designed to be multi-modal; therefore, they're capable of both flight and terrestrial movement.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] To reduce the impact of landing, shock absorbers can be implemented along the wings.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Alternatively, the BFR can pitch up and increase the amount of drag it experiences.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] By increasing the drag force, the BFR will decelerate and minimize the impact upon grounding.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Different land gait patterns can also be implemented.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Bird inspired BFRs can take inspiration from raptors, gulls, and everything in-between.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Bird inspired BFRs can be feathered to increase the angle of attack range over which the prototype can operate before stalling.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The wings of bird inspired BFRs allow for in-plane deformation, and the in-plane wing deformation can be adjusted to maximize flight efficiency depending on the flight gait.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] An example of a raptor inspired BFR is the prototype by Savastano et al.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The prototype has fully deformable flapping wings and is capable of carrying a payload of up to 0.8 kg while performing a parabolic climb, steep descent, and rapid recovery.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The gull inspired prototype by Grant et al. accurately mimics the elbow and wrist rotation of gulls, and they find that lift generation is maximized when the elbow and wrist deformations are opposite but equal.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Insect inspired BFRs typically take inspiration from beetles or dragonflies.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] An example of a beetle inspired BFR is the prototype by Phan and Park, and a dragonfly inspired BFR is the prototype by Hu et al.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The flapping frequency of insect inspired BFRs are much higher than those of other BFRs; this is because of the aerodynamics of insect flight.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Insect inspired BFRs are much smaller than those inspired by mammals or birds, so they are more suitable for dense environments.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The prototype by Phan and Park took inspiration from the rhinoceros beetle, so it can successfully continue flight even after a collision by deforming its hindwings.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Living beings have adapted to a constantly changing environment during evolution through mutation, recombination, and selection.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The core idea of the biomimetic philosophy is that nature's inhabitants including animals, plants, and microbes have the most experience in solving problems and have already found the most appropriate ways to last on planet Earth.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Similarly, biomimetic architecture seeks solutions for building sustainability present in nature.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] While nature serves as a model, there are few examples of biomimetic architecture that aim to be nature positive.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The 21st century has seen a ubiquitous waste of energy due to inefficient building designs, in addition to the over-utilization of energy during the operational phase of its life cycle.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] In parallel, recent advancements in fabrication techniques, computational imaging, and simulation tools have opened up new possibilities to mimic nature across different architectural scales.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] As a result, there has been a rapid growth in devising innovative design approaches and solutions to counter energy problems.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The term biomimetic architecture refers to the study and application of construction principles which are found in natural environments and species, and are translated into the design of sustainable solutions for architecture.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Biomimetic architecture uses nature as a model, measure and mentor for providing architectural solutions across scales, which are inspired by natural organisms that have solved similar problems in nature.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Using nature as a measure refers to using an ecological standard of measuring sustainability, and efficiency of man-made innovations, while the term mentor refers to learning from natural principles and using biology as an inspirational source.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Biomorphic architecture, also referred to as bio-decoration, on the other hand, refers to the use of formal and geometric elements found in nature, as a source of inspiration for aesthetic properties in designed architecture, and may not necessarily have non-physical, or economic functions.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] A historic example of biomorphic architecture dates back to Egyptian, Greek and Roman cultures, using tree and plant forms in the ornamentation of structural columns.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Within biomimetic architecture, two basic procedures can be identified, namely, the bottom-up approach (biology push) and top-down approach (technology pull).
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The boundary between the two approaches is blurry with the possibility of transition between the two, depending on each individual case.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Biomimetic architecture is typically carried out in interdisciplinary teams in which biologists and other natural scientists work in collaboration with engineers, material scientists, architects, designers, mathematicians and computer scientists.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] In the bottom-up approach, the starting point is a new result from basic biological research promising for biomimetic implementation.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] For example, developing a biomimetic material system after the quantitative analysis of the mechanical, physical, and chemical properties of a biological system.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] In the top-down approach, biomimetic innovations are sought for already existing developments that have been successfully established on the market.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The cooperation focuses on the improvement or further development of an existing product.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Researchers studied the termite's ability to maintain virtually constant temperature and humidity in their termite mounds in Africa despite outside temperatures that vary from 1.5 to 40 °C (34.7 to 104.0 °F).
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Researchers initially scanned a termite mound and created 3-D images of the mound structure, which revealed construction that could influence human building design.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The Eastgate Centre, a mid-rise office complex in Harare, Zimbabwe, stays cool via a passive cooling architecture that uses only 10% of the energy of a conventional building of the same size.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Researchers in the Sapienza University of Rome were inspired by the natural ventilation in termite mounds and designed a double façade that significantly cuts down over lit areas in a building.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Scientists have imitated the porous nature of mound walls by designing a facade with double panels that was able to reduce heat gained by radiation and increase heat loss by convection in cavity between the two panels.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The overall cooling load on the building's energy consumption was reduced by 15%.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] A similar inspiration was drawn from the porous walls of termite mounds to design a naturally ventilated façade with a small ventilation gap.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] This design of façade is able to induce air flow due to the Venturi effect and continuously circulates rising air in the ventilation slot.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Significant transfer of heat between the building's external wall surface and the air flowing over it was observed.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The design is coupled with greening of the façade.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Green wall facilitates additional natural cooling via evaporation, respiration and transpiration in plants.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The damp plant substrate further support the cooling effect.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Scientists in Shanghai University were able to replicate the complex microstructure of clay-made conduit network in the mound to mimic the excellent humidity control in mounds.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] They proposed a porous humidity control material (HCM) using sepiolite and calcium chloride with water vapor adsorption-desorption content at 550 grams per meter squared.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Calcium chloride is a desiccant and improves the water vapor adsorption-desorption property of the Bio-HCM.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The proposed bio-HCM has a regime of interfiber mesopores which acts as a mini reservoir.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The flexural strength of the proposed material was estimated to be 10.3 MPa using computational simulations.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] In structural engineering, the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology (EPFL) has incorporated biomimetic characteristics in an adaptive deployable "tensegrity" bridge.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The bridge can carry out self-diagnosis and self-repair.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The arrangement of leaves on a plant has been adapted for better solar power collection.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] These bio-inspired products are sold under the name Flectofin.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Other hingeless bioinspired systems include Flectofold.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Flectofold has been inspired from the trapping system developed by the carnivorous plant *Aldrovanda vesiculosa*.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] There is a great need for new structural materials that are light weight but offer exceptional combinations of stiffness, strength, and toughness.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Such materials would need to be manufactured into bulk materials with complex shapes at high volume and low cost and would serve a variety of fields such as construction, transportation, energy storage and conversion.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] In a classic design problem, strength and toughness are more likely to be mutually exclusive, i.e., strong materials are brittle and tough materials are weak.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] However, natural materials with complex and hierarchical material gradients that span from nano- to macro-scales are both strong and tough.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Generally, most natural materials utilize limited chemical components but complex material architectures that give rise to exceptional mechanical properties.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Understanding the highly diverse and multi functional biological materials and discovering approaches to replicate such structures will lead to advanced and more efficient technologies.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Bone, nacre (abalone shell), teeth, the dactyl clubs of stomatopod shrimps and bamboo are great examples of damage tolerant materials.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The exceptional resistance to fracture of bone is due to complex deformation and toughening mechanisms that operate at spanning different size scales — nanoscale structure of protein molecules to macroscopic physiological scale.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Nacre exhibits similar mechanical properties however with rather simpler structure.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Nacre shows a brick and mortar like structure with thick mineral layer (0.2–0.9 μm) of closely packed aragonite structures and thin organic matrix (~20 nm).
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] While thin films and micrometer sized samples that mimic these structures are already produced, successful production of bulk biomimetic structural materials is yet to be realized.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] However, numerous processing techniques have been proposed for producing nacre like materials.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Pavement cells, epidermal cells on the surface of plant leaves and petals, often form wavy interlocking patterns resembling jigsaw puzzle pieces and are shown to enhance the fracture toughness of leaves, key to plant survival.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Their pattern, replicated in laser-engraved Poly(methyl methacrylate) samples, was also demonstrated to lead to increased fracture toughness.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] It is suggested that the arrangement and patterning of cells play a role in managing crack propagation in tissues.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Biomorphic mineralization is a technique that produces materials with morphologies and structures resembling those of natural living organisms by using bio-structures as templates for mineralization.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Compared to other methods of material production, biomorphic mineralization is facile, environmentally benign and economic.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Various further studies also employed similar methods to produce high strength and high toughness composites involving a variety of constituent phases.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Recent studies demonstrated production of cohesive and self supporting macroscopic tissue constructs that mimic living tissues by printing tens of thousands of heterologous picoliter droplets in software-defined, 3D millimeter-scale geometries.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Efforts are also taken up to mimic the design of nacre in artificial composite materials using fused deposition modelling and the helicoidal structures of stomatopod clubs in the fabrication of high performance carbon fiber-epoxy composites.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Spider silk is tougher than Kevlar used in bulletproof vests.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Engineers could in principle use such a material, if it could be reengineered to have a long enough life, for parachute lines, suspension bridge cables, artificial ligaments for medicine, and other purposes.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The self-sharpening teeth of many animals have been copied to make better cutting tools.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] New ceramics that exhibit giant electret hysteresis have also been realized.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Neuromorphic computers and sensors are electrical devices that copy the structure and function of biological neurons in order to compute.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] One example of this is the event camera in which only the pixels that receive a new signal update to a new state.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] All other pixels do not update until a signal is received.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] In some biological systems, self-healing occurs via chemical releases at the site of fracture, which initiate a systemic response to transport repairing agents to the fracture site.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] To demonstrate the use of micro-vascular networks for autonomic healing, researchers developed a microvascular coating–substrate architecture that mimics human skin.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Bio-inspired self-healing structural color hydrogels that maintain the stability of an inverse opal structure and its resultant structural colors were developed.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] A self-repairing membrane inspired by rapid self-sealing processes in plants was developed for inflatable lightweight structures such as rubber boats or Tensairity constructions.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The researchers applied a thin soft cellular polyurethane foam coating on the inside of a fabric substrate, which closes the crack if the membrane is punctured with a spike.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Self-healing materials, polymers and composite materials capable of mending cracks have been produced based on biological materials.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The self-healing properties may also be achieved by the breaking and reforming of hydrogen bonds upon cyclical stress of the material.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Surfaces that recreate the properties of shark skin are intended to enable more efficient movement through water.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Efforts have been made to produce fabric that emulates shark skin.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Surface tension biomimetics are being researched for technologies such as hydrophobic or hydrophilic coatings and microactuators.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Some amphibians, such as tree and torrent frogs and arboreal salamanders, are able to attach to and move over wet or even flooded environments without falling.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] This kind of organisms have toe pads which are permanently wetted by mucus secreted from glands that open into the channels between epidermal cells.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] They attach to mating surfaces by wet adhesion and they are capable of climbing on wet rocks even when water is flowing over the surface.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Tire treads have also been inspired by the toe pads of tree frogs.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] 3D printed hierarchical surface models, inspired from tree and torrent frogs toe pad design, have been observed to produce better wet traction than conventional tire design.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Marine mussels can stick easily and efficiently to surfaces underwater under the harsh conditions of the ocean.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Mussels use strong filaments to adhere to rocks in the inter-tidal zones of wave-swept beaches, preventing them from being swept away in strong sea currents.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Mussel foot proteins attach the filaments to rocks, boats and practically any surface in nature including other mussels.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] These proteins contain a mix of amino acid residues which has been adapted specifically for adhesive purposes.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Researchers from the University of California Santa Barbara borrowed and simplified chemistries that the mussel foot uses to overcome this engineering challenge of wet adhesion to create copolyampholytes, and one-component adhesive systems with potential for employment in nanofabrication protocols.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Other research has proposed adhesive glue from mussels.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Leg attachment pads of several animals, including many insects (e.g., beetles and flies), spiders and lizards (e.g., geckos), are capable of attaching to a variety of surfaces and are used for locomotion, even on vertical walls or across ceilings.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Attachment systems in these organisms have similar structures at their terminal elements of contact, known as setae.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Such biological examples have offered inspiration in order to produce climbing robots, boots and tape.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Synthetic setae have also been developed for the production of dry adhesives.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Superliquiphobicity refers to a remarkable surface property where a solid surface exhibits an extreme aversion to liquids, causing droplets to bead up and roll off almost instantaneously upon contact.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] This behavior arises from intricate surface textures and interactions at the nanoscale, effectively preventing liquids from wetting or adhering to the surface.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The term "superliquiphobic" is derived from "superhydrophobic," which describes surfaces highly resistant to water.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Superliquiphobic surfaces go beyond water repellency and display repellent characteristics towards a wide range of liquids, including those with very low surface tension or containing surfactants.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Superliquiphobicity emerges when a solid surface possesses minute roughness, forming interfaces with droplets through wetting while altering contact angles.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] This behavior hinges on the roughness factor (Rf), defining the ratio of solid-liquid area to its projection, influencing contact angles.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] On rough surfaces, non-wetting liquids give rise to composite solid-liquid-air interfaces, their contact angles determined by the distribution of wet and air-pocket areas.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The achievement of superliquiphobicity involves increasing the fractional flat geometrical area (fLA) and Rf, leading to surfaces that actively repel liquids.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The inspiration for crafting such surfaces draws from nature's ingenuity, illustrated by the "lotus effect".
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Leaves of water-repellent plants, like the lotus, exhibit inherent hierarchical structures featuring nanoscale wax-coated formations.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Other natural surfaces with these capabilities can include Beetle carapaces, and cacti spines, which may exhibit rough features at multiple size scales.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] These structures lead to superhydrophobicity, where water droplets perch on trapped air bubbles, resulting in high contact angles and minimal contact angle hysteresis.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] This natural example guides the development of superliquiphobic surfaces, capitalizing on re-entrant geometries that can repel low surface tension liquids and achieve near-zero contact angles.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Creating superliquiphobic surfaces involves pairing re-entrant geometries with low surface energy materials, such as fluorinated substances or liquid-like silocones.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] These geometries include overhangs that widen beneath the surface, enabling repellency even for minimal contact angles.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] These surfaces find utility in self-cleaning, anti-icing, anti-fogging, antifouling, enhanced condensation, and more, presenting innovative solutions to challenges in biomedicine, desalination, atmospheric water harvesting, and energy conversion.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] In essence, superliquiphobicity, inspired by natural models like the lotus leaf, capitalizes on re-entrant geometries and surface properties to create interfaces that actively repel liquids.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] These surfaces hold immense promise across a range of applications, promising enhanced functionality and performance in various technological and industrial contexts.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Biomimetic materials are gaining increasing attention in the field of optics and photonics.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] There are still little known bioinspired or biomimetic products involving the photonic properties of plants or animals.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] However, understanding how nature designed such optical materials from biological resources is a current field of research.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] One source of biomimetic inspiration is from plants.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Plants have proven to be concept generations for the following functions; re(action)-coupling, self (adaptability), self-repair, and energy-autonomy.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] As plants do not have a centralized decision making unit (i.e. a brain), most plants have a decentralized autonomous system in various organs and tissues of the plant.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Therefore, they react to multiple stimulus such as light, heat, and humidity.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] One example is the carnivorous plant species *Dionaea muscipula* (Venus flytrap).
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] For the last 25 years, there has been research focus on the motion principles of the plant to develop AVFT (artificial Venus flytrap robots).
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Through the movement during prey capture, the plant inspired soft robotic motion systems.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The fast snap buckling (within 100–300 ms) of the trap closure movement is initiated when prey triggers the hairs of the plant within a certain time (twice within 20 s).
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] AVFT systems exist, in which the trap closure movements are actuated via magnetism, electricity, pressurized air, and temperature changes.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Another example of mimicking plants is the *Pollia condensata,* also known as the marble berry.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The chiral self-assembly of cellulose inspired by the *Pollia condensata* berry has been exploited to make optically active films.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Such films are made from cellulose which is a biodegradable and biobased resource obtained from wood or cotton.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The structural colours can potentially be everlasting and have more vibrant colour than the ones obtained from chemical absorption of light.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] *Pollia condensata* is not the only fruit showing a structural coloured skin; iridescence is also found in berries of other species such as *Margaritaria nobilis*.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] These fruits show iridescent colors in the blue-green region of the visible spectrum which gives the fruit a strong metallic and shiny visual appearance.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The structural colours come from the organisation of cellulose chains in the fruit's epicarp, a part of the fruit skin.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Each cell of the epicarp is made of a multilayered envelope that behaves like a Bragg reflector.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] However, the light which is reflected from the skin of these fruits is not polarised unlike the one arising from man-made replicates obtained from the self-assembly of cellulose nanocrystals into helicoids, which only reflect left-handed circularly polarised light.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The fruit of *Elaeocarpus angustifolius* also show structural colour that come arises from the presence of specialised cells called iridosomes which have layered structures.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Similar iridosomes have also been found in *Delarbrea michieana* fruits.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] In plants, multi layer structures can be found either at the surface of the leaves (on top of the epidermis), such as in *Selaginella willdenowii* or within specialized intra-cellular organelles, the so-called iridoplasts, which are located inside the cells of the upper epidermis.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] For instance, the rain forest plants Begonia pavonina have iridoplasts located inside the epidermal cells.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Structural colours have also been found in several algae, such as in the red alga *Chondrus crispus* (Irish Moss).
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Structural coloration produces the rainbow colours of soap bubbles, butterfly wings and many beetle scales.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Phase-separation has been used to fabricate ultra-white scattering membranes from polymethylmethacrylate, mimicking the beetle *Cyphochilus*.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] LED lights can be designed to mimic the patterns of scales on fireflies' abdomens, improving their efficiency.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Canon Inc.'s SubWavelength structure Coating uses wedge-shaped structures the size of the wavelength of visible light.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The wedge-shaped structures cause a continuously changing refractive index as light travels through the coating, significantly reducing lens flare.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] This imitates the structure of a moth's eye.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Notable figures such as the Wright Brothers and Leonardo da Vinci attempted to replicate the flight observed in birds.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] In an effort to reduce aircraft noise, researchers have looked to the leading edge of owl feathers, which have an array of small finlets or rachis adapted to disperse aerodynamic pressure and provide nearly silent flight to the bird.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Holistic planned grazing, using fencing and/or herders, seeks to restore grasslands by carefully planning movements of large herds of livestock to mimic the vast herds found in nature.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The natural system being mimicked and used as a template is grazing animals concentrated by pack predators that must move on after eating, trampling, and manuring an area, and returning only after it has fully recovered.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Its founder Allan Savory and some others have claimed potential in building soil, increasing biodiversity, and reversing desertification.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] However, many researchers have disputed Savory's claim.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Studies have often found that the method increases desertification instead of reducing it.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Biomimetics can also mean recreating how insects perceive and navigate.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Many insects use skylight polarization patterns to estimate North and geolocate.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] An open-source project has been shown to simulate the measurement of polarization patterns to aid in developing geolocation systems that use them.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The project claims potential future alternatives to traditional GPS systems like GNSS, especially in remote areas and may also be to assist in training neural networks to recognize polarization patterns.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Some air conditioning systems use biomimicry in their fans to increase airflow while reducing power consumption.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Technologists like Jas Johl have speculated that the functionality of vacuole cells could be used to design highly adaptable security systems.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Vacuoles not only isolate threats, contain what's necessary, export waste, maintain pressure—they also help the cell scale and grow.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Johl argues these functions are necessary for any security system design.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The 500 Series Shinkansen used biomimicry to reduce energy consumption and noise levels while increasing passenger comfort.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] With reference to space travel, NASA and other firms have sought to develop swarm-type space drones inspired by bee behavioural patterns, and oxtapod terrestrial drones designed with reference to desert spiders.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Protein folding has been used to control material formation for self-assembled functional nanostructures.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Polar bear fur has inspired the design of thermal collectors and clothing.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The light refractive properties of the moth's eye has been studied to reduce the reflectivity of solar panels.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The Bombardier beetle's powerful repellent spray inspired a Swedish company to develop a "micro mist" spray technology, which is claimed to have a low carbon impact (compared to aerosol sprays).
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The beetle mixes chemicals and releases its spray via a steerable nozzle at the end of its abdomen, stinging and confusing the victim.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Most viruses have an outer capsule 20 to 300 nm in diameter.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Virus capsules are remarkably robust and capable of withstanding temperatures as high as 60 °C; they are stable across the pH range 2–10.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Viral capsules can be used to create nano device components such as nanowires, nanotubes, and quantum dots.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Tubular virus particles such as the tobacco mosaic virus (TMV) can be used as templates to create nanofibers and nanotubes, since both the inner and outer layers of the virus are charged surfaces which can induce nucleation of crystal growth.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] This was demonstrated through the production of platinum and gold nanotubes using TMV as a template.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Mineralized virus particles have been shown to withstand various pH values by mineralizing the viruses with different materials such as silicon, PbS, and CdS and could therefore serve as a useful carriers of material.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] A spherical plant virus called cowpea chlorotic mottle virus (CCMV) has interesting expanding properties when exposed to environments of pH higher than 6.5.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Above this pH, 60 independent pores with diameters about 2 nm begin to exchange substance with the environment.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The structural transition of the viral capsid can be utilized in Biomorphic mineralization for selective uptake and deposition of minerals by controlling the solution pH.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Possible applications include using the viral cage to produce uniformly shaped and sized quantum dot semiconductor nanoparticles through a series of pH washes.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] This is an alternative to the apoferritin cage technique currently used to synthesize uniform CdSe nanoparticles.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] Such materials could also be used for targeted drug delivery since particles release contents upon exposure to specific pH levels.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] In 2025, researchers Yassir Turki and Kilzar Arian proposed the *Multimimicry Regenerative Model (MRM)* as an expanded framework inspired by biomimicry.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The model integrates six interrelated domains—Biomimicry, Chemomimicry, Physicomimicry, Geomimicry, Cosmomimicry, and Semiomimicry—to describe how regenerative processes operate across biological, chemical, physical, geological, cosmological, and semiotic systems.
[src:land-ethic/biomimicry] The MRM seeks to provide a unified scientific and design approach for regenerative innovation.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] A **land ethic** is a philosophy or theoretical framework about how, ethically, humans should regard the land.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] The term was coined by Aldo Leopold (1887–1948) in his *A Sand County Almanac* (1949), a classic text of the environmental movement.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] There he argues that there is a critical need for a "new ethic", an "ethic dealing with human's relation to land and to the animals and plants which grow upon it".
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Leopold offers an ecologically based land ethic that rejects strictly human-centered views of the environment and focuses on the preservation of healthy, self-renewing ecosystems.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] *A Sand County Almanac* was the first systematic presentation of a holistic or ecocentric approach to the environment.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Although Leopold is credited with coining the term "land ethic", there are many philosophical theories that speak to how humans should treat the land.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Some of the most prominent land ethics include those rooted in economics, utilitarianism, libertarianism, egalitarianism, and ecology.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] This is a land ethic based wholly upon economic self-interest.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Leopold sees two flaws in this type of ethic.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] First, he argues that most members of an ecosystem have no economic worth.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] For this reason, such an ethic can ignore or even eliminate these members when they are actually necessary for the health of the biotic community of the land.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] And second, it tends to relegate conservation necessary for healthy ecosystems to the government and these tasks are too large and dispersed to be adequately addressed by such an institution.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] For example, when the US Forest Service was founded by Gifford Pinchot, the prevailing ethos was economic and utilitarian.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Leopold argued for an ecological approach, becoming one of the first to popularize this term coined by Henry Chandler Cowles of the University of Chicago during his early 1900s research at the Indiana Dunes.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Conservation became the preferred term for the more anthropocentric model of resource management, while the writing of Leopold and his inspiration, John Muir, led to the development of environmentalism.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Utilitarianism was most prominently defended by British philosophers Jeremy Bentham and John Stuart Mill.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Though there are many varieties of utilitarianism, generally it is the view that a morally right action is an action that produces the maximum good for people.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Utilitarianism has often been used when deciding how to use land and it is closely connected with an economic-based ethic.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] For example, it forms the foundation for industrial farming; an increase in yield, which would increase the number of people able to receive goods from farmed land, is judged from this view to be a good action or approach.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] In fact, a common argument in favor of industrial agriculture is that it is a good practice because it increases the benefits for humans; benefits such as food abundance and a drop in food prices.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] However, a utilitarian-based land ethic is different from a purely economic one as it could be used to justify the limiting of a person's rights to make a profit.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] For example, in the case of the farmer planting crops on a slope, if the runoff of soil into the community creek led to the damage of several neighbor's properties, then the good of the individual farmer would be overridden by the damage caused to his neighbors.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Thus, while a utilitarian-based land ethic can be used to support economic activity, it can also be used to challenge this activity.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Another philosophical approach often used to guide actions when making (or not making) changes to the land is libertarianism.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Roughly, libertarianism is the ethical view that agents own themselves and have particular moral rights, including the right to acquire the property.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] In a looser sense, libertarianism is commonly identified with the belief that each individual person has a right to a maximum amount of freedom or liberty when this freedom does not interfere with other people's freedom.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] A well-known libertarian theorist is John Hospers.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] For right-libertarians, property rights are natural rights.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Thus, it would be acceptable for the above farmer to plant on a slope as long as this action does not limit the freedom of his or her neighbors.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] This view is closely connected to utilitarianism.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Libertarians often use utilitarian arguments to support their own arguments.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] For example, in 1968, Garrett Hardin applied this philosophy to land issues when he argued that the only solution to the "Tragedy of the Commons" was to place soil and water resources into the hands of private citizens.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Hardin supplied utilitarian justifications to support his argument.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] However, it can be argued that this leaves libertarian-based land ethics open to the above critique lodged against economic-based approaches.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Even excepting this, the libertarian view has been challenged by the critique that numerous people making self-interested decisions often cause large ecological disasters, such as the Dust Bowl disaster.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Even so, libertarianism is a philosophical view commonly held within the United States and, especially, held by U.S. ranchers and farmers.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Egalitarian-based land ethics are often developed as a response to libertarianism.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] This is because, while libertarianism ensures the maximum amount of human liberty, it does not require that people help others.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] It also leads to the uneven distribution of wealth.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] A well-known egalitarian philosopher is John Rawls.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] When focusing on land use, egalitarianism evaluates its uneven distribution and the uneven distribution of the fruits of that land.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] While both a utilitarian- and libertarian-based land ethic could conceivably rationalize this mal-distribution, an egalitarian approach typically favors equality, whether that be an equal entitlement to land or access to food.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] However, there is also the question of negative rights when holding to an egalitarian-based ethic.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] In other words, if it is recognized that a person has a right to something, then someone has the responsibility to supply this opportunity or item; whether that be an individual person or the government.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Thus, an egalitarian-based land ethic could provide a strong argument for the preservation of soil fertility and water because it links land and water with the right to food, the growth of human populations, and the decline of soil and water resources.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Land ethics may also be based upon the principle that the land (and the organisms that live off the land) has intrinsic value.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] These ethics are, roughly, based on an ecological or systems view.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] This position was first put forth by Ayers Brinser in *Our Use of the Land*, published in 1939.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Another example is the deep ecology view, which argues that human communities are built upon a foundation of the surrounding ecosystems or the biotic communities and that all life is of inherent worth.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Similar to egalitarian-based land ethics, the above land ethics were also developed as alternatives to utilitarian and libertarian-based approaches.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Leopold's ethic is one of the most popular ecological approaches in the early 21st century.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Other writers and theorists who hold this view include Wendell Berry (b.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] He also describes it in this way: "The land ethic simply enlarges the boundaries of the community to include soils, waters, plants, and animals, or collectively: the land . . . [A] land ethic changes the role of *Homo sapiens* from conqueror of the land community to plain member and citizen of it.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Leopold was a naturalist, not a philosopher.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] There is much scholarly debate about what exactly Leopold's land ethic asserts and how he argues for it.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Beyond this, scholars disagree about the extent to which Leopold rejected traditional human-centered approaches to the environment and how literally he intended his basic moral maxim to be applied.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] They also debate whether Leopold based his land ethic primarily on human-centered interests, as many passages in *A Sand County Almanac* suggest, or whether he placed significant weight on the intrinsic value of nature.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] However, this interpretation has recently been challenged by Roberta Millstein, who has offered evidence that Darwin's influence on Leopold was not related to Darwin's views about moral sentiments, but rather to Darwin's views about interdependence in the struggle for existence.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Leopold's ecocentric land ethic is popular today with mainstream environmentalists for a number of reasons.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Unlike more radical environmental approaches, such as deep ecology or biocentrism, it does not require huge sacrifices of human interests.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Leopold does not, for example, believe that humans should stop eating or hunting, or experimenting on animals.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Nor does he call for a massive reduction in the human population, or for permitting humans to interfere with nature only to satisfy vital human needs (regardless of economic or other human costs).
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] As an environmental ethic, Leopold's land ethic is a comparatively moderate view that seeks to strike a balance between human interests and a healthy and biotically diverse natural environment.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] A related understanding has been framed as global land as a commons.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] In this view biodiversity and terrestrial carbon storage - an element of climate change mitigation - are global public goods.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Hence, land should be governed on a global scale as a commons, requiring increased international cooperation on nature preservation.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Some critics fault Leopold for lack of clarity in spelling out exactly what the land ethic is and its specific implications for how humans should think about the environment.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] It is clear that Leopold did not intend his basic normative principle ("A thing is right when it tends to preserve the integrity, stability, and beauty of the biotic community") to be regarded as an ethical absolute.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Thus construed, it would prohibit clearing land to build homes, schools, or farms, and generally require a "hands-off" approach to nature that Leopold plainly did not favor.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Presumably, therefore, his maxim should be seen as a general guideline for valuing natural ecosystems and striving to achieve what he terms a sustainable state of "harmony between men and land." But this is vague and, according to some critics, not terribly helpful.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] A second common criticism of Leopold is that he fails to state clearly why we should adopt the land ethic.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] He often cites examples of environmental damage (e.g., soil erosion, pollution, and deforestation) that result from traditional human-centered, "conqueror" attitudes towards nature.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] But it is unclear why such examples support the land ethic specifically, as opposed to biocentrism or some other nature-friendly environmental ethic.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Leopold also frequently appeals to modern ecology, evolutionary theory, and other scientific discoveries to support his land ethic.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Some critics have suggested that such appeals may involve an illicit move from facts to values.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] At a minimum, such critics claim, more should be said about the normative basis of Leopold's land ethic.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Other critics object to Leopold's ecological holism.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] According to animal rights advocate, Tom Regan, Leopold's land ethic condones sacrificing the good of individual animals to the good of the whole, and is thus a form of "environmental fascism." According to these critics, we rightly reject such holistic approaches in human affairs.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Why, they ask, should we adopt them in our treatment of non-human animals?
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Finally, some critics have questioned whether Leopold's land ethic might require unacceptable interferences with nature in order to protect current, but transient, ecological balances.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] If the fundamental environmental imperative is to *preserve* the integrity and stability of natural ecosystems, wouldn't this require frequent and costly human interventions to prevent naturally occurring changes to natural environments?
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] In nature, the "stability and integrity" of ecosystems are disrupted or destroyed all the time by drought, fire, storms, pests, newly invasive predators, etc.
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Must humans act to prevent such ecological changes, and if so, at what cost?
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Why should we place such high value on current ecological balances?
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] Why think it is our role to be nature's steward or policeman?
[src:land-ethic/land-ethic] According to these critics, Leopold's stress on preserving existing ecological balances is overly human-centered and fails to treat nature with the respect it deserves.
